<FIRST>r a AM-SeabrookLicensing     10-14 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Licensing,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Panel Rejects Mass. Request to Reopen Seabrook Inquiry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal regulatory panel rejected a
request by Massachusetts' attorney general to reopen an inquiry
into training at the Seabrook nuclear project because of problems
during low-power testing.
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board on Thursday ruled that
Massachusetts officials had not proven that the June 22 shutdown at
the plant presented a significant safety issue.
   ``The decision reaffirms what we've said since the incident,''
Ron Sher, spokesman for plant operator New Hampshire Yankee, said
Friday.
   Sher said it ``was an isolated situation with no safety
significance, and we took immediate, decisive action to address the
causes of the incident and will continue to ensure safety and
excellence in all plant operations.''
   Seabrook is completed but lacks federal permission to operate
commercially. Plant officials expect to get a license by the end of
the year.
   The utility delayed shutting down the plant after a valve
malfunctioned, despite the urgings of Nuclear Regulatory Commission
inspectors in the control room. Federal and state officials later
criticized control room personnel for the delay.
   New Hampshire Yankee promised that the problem would be
corrected.
   Massachusetts officials argued that the event demonstrated that
plant operators and management ``lack adequate managerial and
administrative controls to operate the facility at any level of
power.'' They argued that a new hearing on a full-power license was
needed because of the relationship between low-power and full-power
operation.
   Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon has been an
outspoken foe of the plant.
   The federal panel said no evidence was presented to raise
legitimate doubts about Seabrook and safety procedures.
   The panel also concluded that the June 22 incident didn't pose a
safety threat and was an aberration. The delay in shutting down the
reactor ``resulted from a narrow omission in training'' and a
misunderstanding, the panel wrote in its decision.
</TEXT>
