<FIRST>r a PM-Fire-TVCrew     10-14 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fire-TV Crew,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Crew Gets Lucky With Big Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A network television news crew arrived in Boston
this week to do a special report on urban fires and quickly found
firefighters battling a Chinatown blaze that was one of the city's
worst in several years.
   ``We've done stories with police around the country where they
say, `Gee, you should have been here last week,''' said Eric
Engberg, a correspondent for the CBS program ``48 Hours.''
   ``This is a case when last week was this week,'' he said.
   The firefighting report, scheduled to air later this month, will
look into fire issues around the country, including arson and
forest fires. Producers picked Boston for a segment on urban fires.
   Engberg said the first fire for the news crew came Wednesday
night, but then on Thursday they followed firefighters to a blaze
in the city's Chinatown section.
   The fire caused an estimated $2 million in damage and became a
downtown spectacle as flames filled a six-story building and
ignited nearly 2,000 pounds of illegal fireworks, setting off
thunderous explosions.
   ``This fire is going to be the star of the show,'' Engberg said.
   Fire officials said a cutting torch used to dismantle a
sprinkler system illegally appeared to have caused the fire. They
said they were trying to determine who cut off the sprinkler system
and who stored the fireworks.
   More than a dozen people suffered minor injuries as a result of
the fire, but no one was seriously hurt, officials said.
</TEXT>
