<FIRST>r w PM-CommunityColleges     10-14 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Community Colleges,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Finds Two-year Colleges Helping Inner Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A videotape produced by the community college
in Jacksonville, Fla., is helping show latchkey children how to
fend for themselves until their parents get home from work.
   A college in Denver is teaching parents of 40 troubled
schoolchildren to read in English to their children. The kids are
doing better in school.
   In Cleveland, the downtown Metro Campus is working with the
Playhouse Square organization to bring brown bag lunch
entertainment to office workers.
   The programs are described in a report made public Friday by an
organization that says they show community colleges in big cities
are doing more than just teaching classes. The report was released
by the Commission on Urban Community Colleges of the American
Association of Community and Junior Colleges.
   ``They are dealing with what I believe to be the very difficult
issues of our times and in many ways go beyond their original
mission and in some sense go beyond what many of us would consider
routine or traditional higher education,'' said Maurice D.
Weidenthal, director of the commission's Urban College Project and
author of the report.
   ``This is not the old campus school for the elite. This is for
youngsters who are at risk,'' said Roscoe Brown Jr., president of
Bronx Community College of the City University of New York.
   Wiedenthal, a former education editor of the Cleveland Press,
visited 10 urban community college campuses.
   ``The study found these campuses to be feisty, solid centers of
learning, with educational images relatively unscathed by the
disappointing performance of nearby school systems or the decay of
surrounding neighborhoods,'' he wrote in this week's issue of the
Community, Technical and Junior College Times.
   The average age of community college students is 30, said Dale
Parnell, president of the association, who said the schools are
getting many people attending the two-year colleges to train for
new jobs.
   Alfred A. DelliBovi, undersecretary of housing and urban
development, attended the commission's press conference and said
community colleges are important to the economies of cities.
   ``When you look at the future of America, which we believe is
going to be one of growth and revival in the cities, there is going
to be a need for training for those new jobs we think are going to
be created,'' he said. ``They require new skills. It's the
community colleges that are right there on the cutting edge
providing those skills.''
   Asked why the Department of Education was not represented at the
news conference, Parnell said: ``They have not taken any interest
in urban education.''
   Lon Anderson, a spokesman for the Education Department, asked
about Parnell's remark, said, ``The facts do not support that
statement in any way, shape or form'' because ``we are doing so
much to focus on at-risk children and inner-city education.''
   Anderson said Secretary of Education Lauro F. Cavazos plans to
visit East Harlem on Monday and Tuesday to attend a conference on
choice in education.
   The schools covered in the report are Bronx Community College,
New York; Miami-Dade Community College, Fla.; Cuyahoga Community
College, Cleveland; Florida Community College, Jacksonville; Penn
Valley Community College, Kansas City; El Centro College, Dallas.
   Also, Los Angeles City College; The Community College of Denver;
The Community College of Allegheny County, Pittsburgh; and Wayne
County Community College, Detroit.
</TEXT>
