<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--BookSale     10-14 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Book Sale,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Collector's Books Fetch $4.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A collection of books and pictures of the former
Ottoman Empire fetched $4.5 million at a three-day auction, nearly
double the pre-sale estimate, Sotheby's said.
   The auction that ended Friday included nearly 5,000 books,
manuscripts, drawings and photographs on the Ottoman lands of
Turkey, Greece, Egypt and the eastern Mediterranean, the auction
house said.
   The highest price was $110,800 for 12 watercolors depicting
views of Constantinople _ the former name of Istanbul _ and the
Bosporus strait. The pictures were published in 1790 and were drawn
by Clara Mayer, daughter of a German or Austrian diplomat.
   The Ottoman Empire, which formed in about 1300, came to an end
in 1920 with the formation of the Turkish republic.
   Sotheby's said the auction was expected to realize about $2.3
million. The collection was owned by U.S. banker Henry Myron
Blackmer II, who died last year.
</TEXT>
