<FIRST>r a PM-People-CarlAlbert     10-14 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Carl Albert,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former House Speaker Honored at Luncheon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMOND, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former House Speaker Carl Albert was
honored as a national leader in the defense of civil rights and
promotion of education who never lost touch with the common folks
back in his native Oklahoma.
   Tears came to the retired congressman's eyes when he got up to
thank his host, former Oklahoma Gov. George Nigh, and Sen. David
Boren, D-Okla.
   ``I am so proud that they have associated their remarks with
me,'' Albert said.
   Albert, 81, a native of Bugtussle, Okla., served in Congress
from 1946 to 1977, and was Speaker of the House from 1971 to 1977.
He was saluted Friday at a luncheon at Central State University.
   Boren said Albert influenced him to go into public service and
counseled him as a young congressman.
   ``After having met with world leaders, Carl Albert never
changed,'' Boren said. ``He still kept up with people in Bugtussle.
He never left spiritually the community that he grew up in.
   ``He never confused his position with his responsibility,''
Boren said.
   Albert once said he drew his greatest satisfaction from his
efforts on behalf of civil rights and education, Boren said.
   ``I am not surprised that Carl Albert would select those two
areas,'' Boren said. ``They are something that is so fundamentally
American.''
</TEXT>
