<DOCNO> AP891014-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CostaRica-Endowment     10-14 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Costa Rica-Endowment,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Endowment Cancels Program That Critics Say Favored Anti-Arias Forces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Endowment for Democracy won't
give money to a Costa Rican political organization because of
questions about the congressionally-funded organization's role in
partisan politics.
   Keith Schuette, president of the National Republican Institute
for International Affairs, the NED's Republican wing, said Friday
the funding for the group ended in July. But he defended the
support for the group, which has strong ties to Costa Rica's main
opposition party.
   ``We view and the endowment views this as within the mandate of
what we've been approved to do,'' he said.
   President Bush will visit Costa Rica later this month for
celebrations marking 100 years of democracy there.
   Papers prepared by Justin Castillo, nephew of Carlos Manuel
Castillo, a member of Arias' National Liberation Party who is
running for president, say the endowment over the past three years
``helped finance opposition party attacks against Costa Rica's
President Oscar Arias and his Nobel Prize-winning peace plan.''
   According to the papers, obtained by The Associated Press, the
endowment backed ``a front organization for the opposition Social
Christian Party.''
   ``There's a fine line here about what is legal. And if it wasn't
illegal, then it certainly was inappropriate,'' Castillo said.
   Arias repeatedly refused calls from the Reagan administration to
take a more active role in denouncing the leftist Sandinista
government in Nicaragua. His peace plan also was cited by Democrats
in Congress as the reason for voting down administration-supported
aid for the Contra rebels fighting the Nicaraguan government.
   The papers said and Schuette confirmed that the Association for
the Defense of Costa Rican Liberty and Democracy received $450,000
over three years from the endowment.
   ``It is ironic,'' the papers assert, that the head of the group,
Rafael Angel Calderon, ``was the recipient in his previous
presidential campaign of $500,000 from Panama's dictator, Gen.
Manuel Noriega.'' The papers cited congressional testimony by Jose
Blandon, a former Noriega aide, for that contention.
   Calderon is a presidential contender for the February elections.
   The National Endowment for Democracy, a nonprofit organization
that receives congressional money, was created in 1983 ``to
strengthen democratic institutions around the world through
non-governmental efforts'' and normally does not finance political
parties or candidates.
   ``We are not allowed to become involved or support a candidate
or campaign,'' Schuette said. Exceptions were made in Grenada,
following the 1983 incursion, and in Nicaragua, with support for
the Conservative Party in 1984.
   The Bush administration has been seeking endowment funds for
Nicaragua's political opposition coalition for February's election.
   Schuette, in a June 5 letter to Carl Gershman, endowment
president, said the Costa Rican program would be changed to avoid
the appearance of impropriety.
   ``While these charges are absolutely untrue,'' he wrote, ``the
re-emergence of such questions at this time is obviously cause for
concern.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
