<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica McClure's family doesn't have any
special plans to celebrate her rescue from a well two years ago,
but their hometown plans to give an award to a city that has
rallied to someone's aid the way Midland did.
   ``I'm fine,'' the 3{-year-old girl said in a brief phone
conversation Thursday night.
   As a toddler, Jessica caught the nation's attention when she
became stuck in a well 22 feet underground. Rescuers struggled for
58 hours to get her free before succeeding on Oct. 16, 1987.
   Jessica doesn't suffer from nightmares or claustrophobia today,
and she walks normally even though her right little toe and the tip
of her right big toe were amputated after the ordeal, said her
father, Chip.
   ``She has no memory of the incident whatsoever,'' he said,
adding that she still gets a sympathy card or two each day.
   The closest thing to an anniversary celebration will be the
announcement of the Midland Community Spirit Award, an annual honor
for a city that has responded to a person or group in need. The
award is unlikely to be ready by Oct. 16 because the judging of
more than 70 entries was incomplete, said Mayor Carroll Thomas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Pauley says she's looking forward to
life after ``Today,'' but the co-anchor of the morning show
declined to say just what she expects to do for NBC's news division.
   ``My horizons have expanded,'' the 13-year ``Today'' veteran
told a group of women managers in a speech Friday. ``It's no longer
Jane Pauley, `Today' show. Now it's Jane Pauley, NBC News. Imagine
the possibilities.''
   Pauley's future has been the subject of speculation since NBC
``Sunrise'' anchor Deborah Norville, 31, moved up to ``Today'' as
news anchor in August, swapping duties with John Palmer.
   The 38-year-old Pauley, who is paid $1.2 million a year and has
two years left on her contract, told The Washington Post earlier
this week she intends to stay with the network, but will probably
leave ``Today'' by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The show goes on for pop music star Elton John
after fatigue and illness forced him to cancel an appearance
earlier this week.
   John spent several days of rest preparing to resume his
35-concert North American tour Friday in Miami, publicist Dione
Dirito said.
   The veteran British rocker canceled a performace in Tampa on
Tuesday because of exhaustion and influenza. A show rescheduled for
the following night also was called off.
   ``He's better and the tour is continuing,'' said Ms. Dirito.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Andrew Dice Clay was
arrested for trespassing at a restaurant after the owner, who
accused him of causing a ruckus there earlier, tried to kick him
out, authorities said.
   Clay was arrested early Friday at the Ben Frank Restaurant after
refusing the manager's demands to leave, Sheriff's Deputy George
Ducoulombier said.
   The manager, who wasn't identified, made a citizen's arrest and
deputies booked the 32-year-old comedian from New York City. He was
released after promising to appear in court Nov. 3 on the
misdemeanor charge.
   The manager accused Clay of causing a scene at the eatery
several years ago, the deputy said, but he didn't have specifics.
Clay recently was banned from MTV after he swore during a live
televised broadcast of the MTV Video Music Awards.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Holly Dunn's induction into
the Grand Ole Opry as its 64th member will cap festivities marking
the 64th anniversary of the country music show today.
   Dunn, whose hit ``Daddy's Hands'' was originally written as a
Father's Day gift and first recorded by the Whites, is the first
new Opry member since Ricky Van Shelton and Patty Loveless joined
in June 1988.
   The 32-year-old San Antonio native won the Country Music
Association's Horizon Award for promising newcomers in 1987. She
also was named the Academy of Country Music's Top New Female
Vocalist in 1986 and has been a frequent guest on the Opry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The award-winning country music group
Highway 101 is taking an 18-month break from performing together,
but three of the four musicians plan to form a trio.
   The group, whose hits include, ``Do You Love Me, Just Say Yes''
and ``Cry, Cry, Cry,'' won the Country Music Association's group of
the year award Monday for the second straight year.
   Backstage after the show, the four said group member Paulette
Carlson will record a solo album. The remaining three _ Cactus
Moser, Curtis Stone and Jack Daniels _ plan to cut an album of
their own under a new name that has yet to be chosen.
   They have been together since the mid-1980s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Sheldon will marry advertising
executive Alexandra Kostoff in a Las Vegas ceremony this weekend,
his publicist said.
   The 72-year-old novelist and screenwriter and Ms. Kostoff
planned to hold the ceremony today at the Caesar's Palace hotel,
publicist Skip Heinecke announced Friday. It will be the second
marriage for both.
   The couple will honeymoon in New York City, where Sheldon will
turn over the manuscript of his tenth novel, ``Memories of
Midnight,'' to his publisher, William Morrow. They then will visit
New England.
   Sheldon's best-selling novels include ``Rage of Angels,'' ``The
Sands of Time'' and ``Master of the Game.'' The onetime director
and screenwriter created the television series, ``I Dream of
Jeannie'' and ``Hart to Hart.''
   He won an Oscar in 1947 for best original screenplay for ``The
Bachelor and the Bobby-soxer,'' starring Shirley Temple.
