<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     10-14 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former GSA Chief Says Pierce Meeting Led to Grant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel investigating abuses at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development has received its
strongest allegation yet that former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce
took a direct role on behalf of politically connected developers.
   Former General Services Administrator Gerald Carmen testified
Friday that he met only with Pierce _ once a former colleague of
his _ in seeking tax credits and rental subsidies to develop an
apartment rehabilitation project in Arlington, Texas.
   About six weeks after the meeting in Pierce's office, Pierce's
executive assistant, Deborah Gore Dean, and then-Federal Housing
Commissioner Thomas Demery approved Carmen's 316-unit Pebble Creek
project for funding.
   But the approval in a March 4, 1987 memo occurred more than a
month before the local Arlington Public Housing Authority even
filed an application to HUD, according to agency documents.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said Friday the paper trail and
Carmen's testimony contradict Pierce's statement to the
subcommittee last spring that he took no part in project decisions.
   ``I don't want to concede that, although I do concede that's the
way it looks,'' Carmen told Lantos' House Government Operations
employment and housing subcommittee.
   However, Carmen added, ``I'm a little surprised at the way it
went and I find myself a little uncomfortable at the position I'm
in now.''
   Carmen's testimony occurred in the 20th subcommittee hearing
that Lantos had held over six months into influence peddling,
mismanagement and alleged fraud at HUD during the eight years
Pierce was a member of President Reagan's Cabinet.
   In his last appearance before the subcommittee in September,
Pierce cited his Fifth Amendment rights on self-incrimination and
refused to answer any questions. The panel has subpoenaed Pierce to
testify again later this month and in November.
   In his testimony, Carmen acknowledged the Texas project has
already returned $800,000 in profits to him through up-front tax
credits although he put up no money of his own.
   At the time, Carmen said, he saw the 316-unit Pebble Creek
Moderate Rehabilitation Program project as an opportunity to both
``make money and do some good'' by providing rent-subsidized
housing to poor people in Arlington.
   Formerly a Manchester, N.H., businessman, Carmen worked with
Pierce during the transition between the Carter and Reagan
administrations after the 1980 election. Carmen was a member of
Reagan's transition team for HUD, and Pierce was named to be the
department's secretary.
   Carmen was appointed to head the General Services
Administration, which is responsible for building or leasing most
government offices and acting as a supply officer for much of the
federal bureaucracy. He held the GSA post until 1984, when Reagan
named him U.S. ambassador to United Nations agencies in Geneva,
Switzerland.
   As in other cases where projects were pushed by Washington
insiders, local Arlington officials were unaware of the potential
for the apartment project before he approached them, Carmen said.
   Pebble Creek was developed as a limited partnership between
Carmen and Joshua Muss, a law partner of Carmen's daughter.
   Carmen and Muss used HUD guaranteed mortgages to borrow $8.2
million _ $4 million for buying a rundown apartment complex and $4
million to upgrade it _ and sharing in $2.4 million in up front tax
credits plus $1.8 million in annual HUD rent subsidies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
