<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonStandoff 1stLd-Writethru a0405 10-14 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Standoff, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0405,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Killer Slain as Prison Guards Save Hostage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 4-5, `Prison officials ... go in' to UPDATE
with prison director's explanation for storming room; picks up 4th graf,
`Larry Henry ...' SUBS 6th graf, `The decision ...' to conform. SUBS penultimate
graf, `Prison officials ...' to UPDATE with officials now saying Meller
didn't tie himself to hostage.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted killer who held a female
doctor hostage for 10 hours in a prison infirmary Friday was shot
to death by sheriff's deputies who stormed into the room,
authorities said.
   Kenneth James Meller, 48, was shot after the officers tossed a
concussion grenade into the office and rushed in. ``Meller made
some sort of move. He's dead,'' said Terry Hubert, a spokesman for
the Northern Nevada Correctional Center.
   Hubert added that Dr. Karen Gedney was ``a bit stunned by the
grenade'' but otherwise unharmed.
   Prison officials said that during the ordeal, Meller talked
about committing suicide on Saturday, exactly 14 years after he
shot and killed a Nevada Highway Patrol trooper following a bank
robbery.
   State Prison Director Ron Angelone said Meller didn't threaten
Dr. Gedney ``until the end. As it was going downhill, he said that
if anyone showed his face he would hurt her. At that point we
decided to go in.''
   Larry Henry, Gov. Bob Miller's press secretary, said he was told
that the deputies rushed into the doctor's office through a door
and a window.
   ``The plan was to isolate the man from the woman. They tried to
catch him, there were a couple of shots, and he got hit,'' Henry
said.
   The decision to storm the room followed lengthy negotiations
with Meller that involved Warden Brenda Burns, Angelone and the
local sheriff, Paul McGrath.
   Meller had gone into the medium-security prison's infirmary
about 10 a.m., scuffled with staffers and then took Gedney hostage,
saying he was thinking about killing himself.
   Prison officials said Meller had a 4-inch knife. Prison
spokesman Glen Warton said earlier reports that Meller had tied
himself to Gedney were incorrect. Meller had a telephone and had
been in constant contact with officials who could see him through
windows in the infirmary. He made no demands.
   Meller was serving a no-parole life term for killing a Nevada
Highway Patrol trooper at Lake Tahoe in 1975. He had no record of
previous trouble in the prison system.
</TEXT>
