<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WeaponsPlan     10-14 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weapons Plan,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Reconsidering Key Parts of Weapons Modernization Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is reconsidering key
parts of an $81 billion plan for revitalizing the nation's nuclear
weapons complex, including a proposal for building a new plutonium
refinery in Idaho, officials said.
   The plan, unveiled in the final days of the Reagan
administration, was billed as a 20-year blueprint for modernizing
the weapons plants, which are plagued by mechanical breakdowns,
safety flaws and widespread environmental problems.
   Since then, the breadth and depth of the problems have
increased, and Energy Secretary James D. Watkins has tried to
overhaul the weapons program to focus more on safety and
environmental issues.
   In a Sept. 29 internal memorandum made available to The
Associated Press on Friday, Watkins said he was creating a
committee of defense specialists to review the recommendations of
the December 1988 modernization plan prepared by his predecessor,
John Herrington, as well as its underlying assumptions.
   Watkins made clear he was unhappy with some elements of the
Herrington blueprint, although he did not say what changes he
wanted. He made no mention of costs.
   ``They did not adequately address some of the serious problems
that have since been identified particularly with respect to
environmental and waste management issues,'' Watkins wrote.
   ``Based on my review of these results, I am not satisfied that
the assumptions upon which the study was based are valid when
reviewed by today's standards,'' he said, adding he was ordering
``a hard relook at this whole issue.''
   Watkins did not spell out exactly what parts of the 2010 Report
he did not like. He said John Tuck, the No. 3 official in the
department, would head the review committee, which also includes
representatives of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the National
Security Council.
   One official involved in the review, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the group would present a report to Watkins' office
on Monday recommending a set of assumptions upon which to develop a
new modernization blueprint.
   A final report to Watkins on modernization recommendations is
due next April 2.
   The official said one assumption under review is the need for a
Special Isotope Separation plant, which would convert existing
supplies of fuel-grade plutonium to a grade suitable for
thermonuclear warheads. Critics have questioned the need for the
plant in light of adequate existing supplies of plutonium. It would
be built at the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory.
   Another proposal under review is a plan to build two new
tritium-producing reactors _ one at the Idaho laboratory and the
other at the Savannah River weapons plant, near Aiken, S.C., the
official said. They would replace three aging and currently
shut-down Savannah River reactors that make the tritium needed for
nuclear warheads.
   Many members of Congress have said budget constraints are likely
to kill at least one of the planned reactors.
   Among other elements of the 2010 Report now under review, the
official said, are:
   _Ending all operations at the Rocky Flats plant near Denver and
transferring its plutonium-processing activities to other
facilities. The main reason is its proximity to a major urban
center. The FBI currently is investigating alleged environmental
violations at the plant.
   _Phasing out the Fernald uranium-processing plant near
Cincinnati and transferring most of its operations to other sites.
The official said this could begin as early as next year. The plant
has been shut down since last summer because of environmental
problems, and no resumption date has been announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
