<FIRST>r a PM-RecruitSuicide     10-14 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Recruit Suicide,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Recruit Kills Himself After Failing Last-Chance Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young recruit who worked three years to
qualify for the police force shot himself to death at a firing
range after flunking his final chance at a marksmanship test.
   Daniel Morales, 21, was firing at the third and final target at
the Police Training Academy when he briefly pointed his .357
revolver at an examiner, then turned the gun to his head and shot
himself, Police Capt. George Hegerty said.
   Police said Morales' best score on the tests was 203. The
minimum required is 210 out of a possible 300.
   Morales was the only recruit at the firing range at the time,
police said. He died in a hospital almost seven hours later.
   Morales had attended Milwaukee Tech to help qualify for the
academy. He was promoted to officer recruit Aug. 20 and was
assigned to a class that graduates in January.
   He resigned Sept. 29 after failing a shooting test but appealed
for another chance after a vision examination indicated he needed
glasses, assistant city attorney Thomas C. Goeldner said.
   Acting chief Le Roy A. Jahnke had given Morales until Friday to
pass the marksmanship test. He had spent more than a week in
remedial firearms training, Goeldner said.
   After the shooting, the other 41 members of Morales' class met
to listen to counselors.
   ``We're as close as family here,'' police inspector Joseph A.
Kalivoda said. ``I've lost officers before and it never gets any
easier.''
</TEXT>
