<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Spending-Taxes Bjt   10-14 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending-Taxes, Bjt,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate OKs $14 Billion Deficit-Cut Bill, Puts Off Capital Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and President Bush are facing two
impending budget struggles following Senate passage of a $14
billion deficit-reduction bill that was stripped clean of billions
of dollars of spending items and tax breaks.
   The chamber's 87-7 passage of the fiscal 1990 deficit-cutting
legislation late Friday set the stage for what could be difficult
negotiations between the Senate and House on a compromise version
of the bill.
   Unless Bush signs the compromise into law by Monday _ impossible
because House members are away for the weekend _ $16 billion in
defense and domestic spending cuts will take effect that day. The
fiscal year began Oct. 1.
   The deal worked out between Democratic and Republican leaders
also left the bill minus a capital gains tax cut that has been a
priority for Bush, putting off that partisan showdown.
   Most members of the Senate _ which the Democrats dominate 55-45
_ favor a capital gains reduction, but Republicans were unable to
gather the 60 votes they needed to get that measure attached to the
deficit bill.
   ``We're putting aside capital gains today, but I can promise ...
we'll be back, ready to win, ready to prevail at the earliest
opportunity,'' said Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas.
   ``This was a major defeat for the president,'' Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell of Maine told reporters later. He said the
administration ``expended more energy and effort'' on the capital
gains fight than it had on any issue this year.
   After a week of contentious debate, senators agreed to pare the
legislation to items that raise $5.3 billion in taxes and cut about
$8.7 billion in spending. Gone were expanded child care efforts, an
extension of the 3 percent tax on telephone calls, new programs to
promote sales of crops ranging from soybeans to kiwi fruit and
other provisions.
   The deal was cemented shortly before final passage when senators
voted by voice to strip the so-called extraneous items from the
bill, slicing the legislation from 1,376 pages to about 200.
   ``We're putting a deficit-reduction bill back in the category of
being a deficit-reduction bill,'' said Senate Budget Committee
Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn.
   Lawmakers are likely to renew their fight over items that don't
make the final House-Senate compromise bill in new tax legislation
Congress will consider, probably in two or three weeks, senators
said.
   The bill contains about two dozen new or increased taxes, mostly
on corporations.
   Departing international air travelers would face a doubling of
the current $3 tax, some farm workers would have income taxes
withheld for the first time, and a new tax would be imposed on
producers of chemicals that destroy the ozone layer of the
atmosphere.
   The measure also would cut Medicare spending by more than $2
billion, mainly by reducing payments to doctors and hospitals.
   It also is rife with gimmicky provisions Congress and Bush
agreed to months ago. Nearly $1.8 billion in claimed savings come
from no longer counting the Postal Service's operating losses in
budget calculations. Hundreds of millions of more in ``savings''
arise from shifting payments planned for this year into future
years.
   The House passed its own $11 billion version of the measure _
containing dozens of special-interest provisions of its own _ on
Oct. 5.
   That measure contained a two-year capital gains tax cut, a child
care expansion, a rollback of year-old Medicare benefits for
elderly patients who need lengthy hospital stays, and new Medicaid
initiatives.
   Congressional leaders have said they expect the automatic cuts
under Gramm-Rudman to be rolled back when the deficit-reduction
bill is signed into law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;LBailouts     10-14 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L Bailouts,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Large S&amp;Ls Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are advancing $7.1 billion
to help the buyers of four large insolvent savings institutions in
the first major deals struck since Congress enacted a $50 billion
bailout plan.
   The sales of thrifts in Houston, Pennsylvania, Florida and
California were announced late Friday by the Resolution Trust
Corp., created Aug. 9 when President Bush signed the bailout bill.
   NCNB, an aggressive regional bank holding company headquartered
in Charlotte, N.C., purchased two of the thrifts offered by the RTC.
   A third thrift was sold to a Canadian savings institution and
the fourth was sold another to Meridian Bancorp. of Reading, Pa.
   RTC executive director David C. Cook said a fifth large thrift,
Peoples Heritage Savings of Salina, Kan., had been scheduled for
sale but was not sold because the bids submitted were unacceptable.
   The four institutions sold, the new owner, and the amount of
government cash advanced are:
   _University Federal Savings Association, Houston, acquired by
NCNB Texas National Bank, $3.8 billion.
   _Hill Financial Savings Association, Red Hill, Pa., purchased by
Meridian, $1.9 billion.
   _Freedom Savings and Loan Association, Tampa, Fla., acquired by
NCNB National Bank of Florida, $875 million.
   _Pacific Savings Bank, Costa Mesa, Calif., taken over by Royal
Trustco Limited of Toronto, $550 million.
   The buyers are putting up a total of $2.33 billion to purchase
some of the sound loans and other assets of the institutions, and
they are paying the government a combined $224.9 million to take
over deposits of the failed thrifts.
   They have also agreed to put up enough additional money to bring
the S&amp;Ls into compliance with capital standards, RTC spokesman
Steven Katsanos said.
   The government is retaining ``bad'' assets _ repossessed real
estate and sour loans _ with a book value of $2.33 billion. It
hopes to recover some of its $7.1 billion outlay by selling those
assets.
   Normal operating hours are continuing at Peoples Heritage and
the four institutions sold.
   The five institutions, particularly Peoples Heritage, University
Federal and Hill Financial, strayed from traditional S&amp;L lending
for single-family mortgages, concentrating instead on speculative
construction and development lending for large commercial and
residential projects, Ely said.
   Prior to Friday's sales, the RTC had closed 27 small S&amp;Ls. The
RTC has more than 250 S&amp;Ls in its control and expects as many as
300 others will fail in the next three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
