<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     10-14 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Rebel Leader Returns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pedro Joaquin Chamorro Barrios, a
former leader of the U.S.-backed Contra rebels, returned to
Nicaragua to help his mother's opposition presidential campaign.
   Chamorro Barrios arrived in Managua Friday night from Costa Rica
and, like all returning rebels, signed a document when he
re-entered Nicaragua that says he accepts a government amnesty and
belongs to no armed group.
   ``I'm coming to help my mother as much as I can,'' Chamorro, 38,
told reporters at the airport.
   Violeta Chamorro, publisher of the newspaper La Prensa, is the
candidate of the United National Opposition coalition, and
President Daniel Ortega's main challenger in Feb. 25, 1990,
elections. Ortega, of the Sandinista National Liberation Front, is
running for another five-year term.
   Chamorro Barrios was the fifth former Nicaraguan Resistance
leader to return to Nicaragua under a repatriation program called
for in a regional peace accord signed by five Central American
presidents. The others were Alfredo Cesar, Azucena Ferrey, Roberto
Ferrey and Alfonso Robelo.
   More than 500 rebels also have returned.
   Chamorro Barrios resigned as a director of the resistance in
1988 after the U.S. government stopped weapons shipments to the
Contras. The United States continues to supply the rebels with
humanitarian aid.
   Under the Aug. 7 regional agreement, the estimated 12,000 rebels
are to be disbanded from camps along Honduras' border with
Nicaragua by mid-December. In exchange, President Daniel Ortega
moved national elections up to Feb. 25 and promised that
campaigning and voting will be free and fair, with no restrictions
on the press.
   Chamorro Barrios is a founder of the Social Democratic Party,
one of the 13 parties in the opposition coalition.
   He said he would not rejoin La Prensa, which he ran before going
into exile in Costa Rica in March 1985, but would work as an
independent journalist. Chamorro Barrios said he planned to write
articles for the U.S. newspaper Diario de Las Americas and will
continue his commentaries for Channel 23 television in Miami.
   His father, newspaper editor Pedro Joaquin Chamorro Cardenal,
was a strong critic of former President Anastasio Somoza. Chamorro
Cardenal's January 1978 assassination broadened support for the
Sandinista revolution that overthrew Somoza in July 1979, ending
the Somoza family's 42-year rule.
   La Prensa now is the only daily in Nicaragua that opposes the
Sandinistas. Mrs. Chamorro served on the first post-revolutionary
junta but resigned after a year and joined the opposition, citing
the Sandinistas move to the left and its links with Cuba and the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
