<SECOND>PM-BRF--DEA Arrests,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Arrested in Undercover DEA Drug Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug Enforcement Administration undercover
agents have arrested two District of Columbia men after the pair
attempted to buy cocaine with an estimated street value of $1.5
million, an official says.
   Ricardo Bernard Smith, 22, and Michael F. Johnson, 20, were
charged at 11:30 p.m. Friday with possession, distribution and
conspiracy to distribute cocaine, Mario Perez, a spokesman for the
DEA's Washington Field Division, said early today.
   The two were finalizing a transaction with the undercover agents
to buy 33 pounds, or 15 kilos, of cocaine, when they were arrested
at the Radisson Hotel in Alexandria, Va., across the Potomac River
from the nation's capital, said Perez.
   The pair had agreed during earlier negotiations to pay $231,000
for the cocaine from an unidentified agent who was posing as a
cocaine supply source, the spokesman said. Smith told the agent
Friday that he had $160,000 cash and offered his 1989 Porsche and a
Rolex watch to make up the difference, Perez said.
   Johnson and Smith were being held without bond in the Alexandria
jail and were scheduled to appear before a U.S. Magistrate on
Monday, said Perez.
