<FIRST>u a AM-MarcosMass 3rdLd-Writethru a0438 10-14 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos Mass, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0438,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Funeral Mass Said in Honolulu</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with eulogy; picks up 2nd graf
a0433, `Marcos' coffin...' SUBS 5th graf, `A standing-room ...' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos was eulogized by a long-time
supporter Friday as a person much like Jesus Christ _ betrayed by
the misguided will of the people but forgiving to those who had
wronged him.
   ``Christ was a victim of the people's power, so Marcos was a
victim of the people's power,'' said Roman Catholic Monsignor
Domingo Nebres of the Philippines, referring to the 1986 ``people
power'' revolt that ended Marcos' dictatorial rule and forced him
into exile in Hawaii.
   ``My dear beloved president would say, `Do not cry for me ...
cry for your country,'' Nebres told the 1,500 family members,
dignitaries and supporters who packed the Co-Cathedral of St.
Theresa, the largest Roman Catholic church in Honolulu.
   The funeral Mass took place even as it remained uncertain where
the former Philippine president will be buried.
   Marcos' coffin, draped with a Philippine flag, arrived at about
6:30 p.m. borne by 10 pallbearers wearing white Philippine military
uniforms and black armbands. All were former Philippine military
officials, including Col. Arturo Aruiza, Marcos' closest adviser
during his three-year exile in Hawaii.
   Marcos' widow, Imelda, was accompanied by two of her children,
Ferdinand ``Bong Bong'' Marcos Jr. and daughter Irene Araneta, as
well as other relatives.
   Mrs. Marcos was clad entirely in black, including a black veil
covering her face, and clutched a silver rosary. She did not answer
reporters' questions.
   A standing-room only crowd filled the Co-Cathedral of St.
Theresa. Dozens of people waited outside the church, trying to peer
inside.
   Mrs. Marcos sat in the front row as Marcos' coffin was brought
to the front of the church. Aruiza stood at full military rest near
Marcos, whose casket was surrounded by white flowers.
   The body was to be returned to Nuuanu Mortuary for entombment
Sunday at the Valley of the Temples Memorial Park.
   At least eight Marcos security guards, as well as two Honolulu
police officers on special duty and an unknown number of FBI agents
attended the service.
   ``We are most concerned about making sure the service is
dignified and to protect the people inside,'' said Rev. Daniel
McNichol, the church's rector.
   Philippine Consul General to Hawaii Tomas Gomez said there were
no official representatives of his government at the funeral.
However, several Philippine congressmen attended, including former
Labor Minister Blas Ople and Congressman Roquito Ablan Jr., said
Marcos supporter Joe Lazo.
   Lazo also said Christina Ponce Enrile, wife of Sen. Juan Ponce
Enrile, the former defense minister, would attend, as well as the
wife of Philippine Gen. Fabian Ver, Marcos' right-hand man during
his rule. Fabian Ver's whereabouts are unknown and he is a fugitive
from justice.
   Marcos, who ruled the Philippines for 20 years, died here Sept.
28 following a long illness.
   Supporters are constructing what they call a temporary resting
place for Marcos' body, which has been at his hillside
home-in-exile since the day of his death.
   Work continued Friday on the air-conditioned shed at Valley of
the Temples Memorial Park. Marcos family spokesman Arturo Aruiza
said he expects the wood and corrugated metal structure to be
completed by Sunday, when Marcos' remains are to be moved to the
cemetery.
   Mrs. Marcos has vowed to bury him in the Philippines but
Philippine President Corazon Aquino has banned his return, even in
death.
   The Philippine government Friday claimed Marcos' family has
plotted to kill Mrs. Aquino and asked the Supreme Court to uphold
her ban on returning his body to the Philippines for burial.
   The claim was made in a brief filed with the court asking it to
reject a petition by Marcos supporters to allow members of Marcos'
family to return his remains from Hawaii.
   Marcos was ousted in a 1986 popular revolt that catapulted Mrs.
Aquino to power. He was exiled to Hawaii, where he was subsequently
indicted by the U.S. government for allegedly looting his nation's
treasury.
   Mrs. Marcos has said having her husband's body entombed above
ground in the guarded shed would make it easier to return his
remains to the Philippines if Mrs. Aquino changes her mind, or if
the Philippine Supreme Court overturns the ban.
</TEXT>
