<HEAD>Alleged IRA Member Says Extradition Denial Proves His Innocence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Roman Catholic priest sought by
Britain for his alleged links with the IRA said Ireland's refusal
to extradite him was a de facto acquittal.
   Patrick Ryan said Friday that he is now ``innocent in the eyes
of the law.''
   The government said Thursday that Ryan, 59, will not be
prosecuted because material submitted by Britain to bring him to
trial was insufficient.
   Britain tried to secure Ryan's extradition on charges of murder
and bombing conspiracy and explosives possession on the British
mainland from 1975 to 1988. The Irish Republican Army, outlawed in
Britain and Ireland, is fighting a guerrilla campaign to drive the
British out of Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated
province with Ireland, which is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
