<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0442 10-14 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Chief Submits $1.9 Billion Budget; Chides Deadbeats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd pvs, `As it...' to RESTORE time element; picks up 4th
pvs, `Perez de...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
proposed a two-year budget of $1.98 billion and scolded nations
that don't pay their dues.
   He did not single out any countries, but the United States tops
the list of 66 deadbeats with a debt of more than $495 million as
of Sept. 30.
   As it is, the world body has barely enough money to meet
expenses through the end of the month, the U.N. chief said Friday.
   Perez de Cuellar said his 1990-91 budget projection, given to
the General Assembly committee that handles budgetary affairs,
``represents a negative rate of real growth of 0.4 percent.''
   Under the plan, personnel would be reduced by 12 percent and
their would be either no change or a reduction in most expenses,
including travel for staff and consultants.
   ``The only increases in expenditures relate to strictly mandated
activities, notably construction of new premises and technological
innovations,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   But the United will face insolvency if not all of the 159 member
nations pay their dues, he said.
   ``The situation is ominous. As of yesterday, only 66 member
states had paid their assessments for 1989 in full and had no
contributions outstanding for prior years,'' he said. ``Outstanding
contributions to the regular budget _ including arrears _ amounted
to $603.8 million.''
   Perez de Cuellar said the United Nations has $68 million left in
its General Fund, an amount barely sufficient to cover expenditures
through October.
   U.S. congressional subcommittees have given preliminary approval
for payment of $205.5 million toward the full 1990 fiscal year
assessment of $216 million. They rejected State Department requests
for $46 million more to pay about 10 percent of the arrears, citing
U.S. budgetary constraints.
   Beginning in 1985, the Reagan administration began withholding
U.S. dues to protest what it said was anti-Western bias,
inefficiency and budget overruns.
   In September 1988, Reagan said U.N. austerity measures warranted
payment of back dues, a job passed to the Bush administration.
</TEXT>
