<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Market-Economy 1stLd-Writethru 10417 10-14 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, 10417,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Seeks to Calm Economic Fears</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to add dropped word `official.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is
reassuring the nation the largest decline in the stock market since
the 1987 crash will not hurt the real economy that provides
Americans with jobs and stable prices.
   ``The outlook is good for continued moderate growth,'' said
Brady, who issued a statement two hours after the market closed
Friday.
   He was the only senior government official to comment on the
stunning almost 191-point drop of the Dow Jones industrial average.
   President Bush refused to answer reporters' shouted questions
while boarding a helicopter at the White House on his way to his
Camp David retreat in Maryland.
   A spokesman for the Federal Reserve Board said the central bank
would have no comment. Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman
Richard Breeden, in his second full day on the job, was equally
tight-lipped.
   ``Today's decline ... should be viewed in the context of a
591-point rise since Jan. 1, 1989,'' Brady said.
   ``It's important to recognize that today's stock market decline
doesn't signal any fundamental change in the condition of the
economy,'' he said. ``The economy remains well balanced and the
outlook is for continued moderate growth.''
   Private economists generally agreed, even though the Labor
Department said Friday that wholesale inflation shot up a worrisome
0.9 percent in September. Analysts said the increase was due
largely to a one-time climb in energy prices and a statistical
fluke in the measurement of auto prices.
   Also, economists pointed to an unexpected 0.5 percent rise in
retail sales last month as evidence the economy, although growing
more slowly than last year, retained some strength.
   Traders said the stock plummet was triggered by the failure of a
management-labor group to arrange financing for a takeover of
United Airlines' parent company. That hurt takeover-related stocks,
which in turn dragged down the market generally.
   ``I think it's a one-day panic,'' said economist David Wyss of
DRI-McGraw Hill, a Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm. ``I think
it's fairly clear the drop was caused by the (United Airlines)
deal.''
   Nevertheless, analysts said the market turmoil will further
pressure the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates. The central
bank has preferred to focus on containing inflation with high
interest rates, but that may soon change, according to analysts.
   ``The Federal Reserve, just as it did in 1987, will move to pump
liquidity into the system and push interest rates significantly
lower,'' said economist David Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., a
government securities dealer in New York.
   ``I'm expecting the Fed will ease perhaps a full percentage
point within the next few weeks,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the
Senate Banking Committee, said he was concerned that market trading
systems be ready to handle heavy volume on Monday. He said he
received one report of market makers in the over-the-counter market
_ brokers who normally stand ready to buy or sell specific stocks
not listed on an exchange _ refusing to answer their telephones
late Friday.
   ``That's disturbing,'' Riegle said. ``I think one of the lessons
of two years ago is that it's very important that market makers be
in place and that there be sufficient liquidity to handle whatever
the volume is.''
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., who chairs the subcommittee
overseeing market regulation, used the crash to renew his campaign
for restructuring market regulation.
   ``This is the second heart attack, two years after the first.
It's about time we made the changes necessary to avoid a third,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike Bjt   10-14 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Secretary Brings Company, Union Heads Together in Coal Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole steered the
heads of Pittston Co. and the United Mine Workers to their first
meeting since a bitter strike began six months ago, saying ``it's
time to start the healing.''
   Mrs. Dole said Friday she believed face-to-face talks between
Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas and UMW President Richard Trumka
were the only way to break the long stalemate.
   ``I'm not a mediator. I'm not here to say I have the answer to
this complex problem, but I do feel now it is time to see if we can
facilitate the bargaining process,'' she said. ``Ultimately, it has
to be resolved between the private parties.''
   The labor secretary announced she had arranged the meeting for
this afternoon in her Washington office after a fact-finding trip
to the coal fields.
   Douglas and Trumka haven't met since 1,695 miners in Virginia,
West Virginia and Kentucky went on strike April 5 against Pittston
Coal Group Inc.
   Face-to-face talks between lower-level negotiators broke off
June 7. They resumed in July, but have regressed to the point where
negotiators for the company and union are meeting a few days a
month in separate rooms with a federal mediator shuttling messages
back and forth.
   The strike has crippled production at Pittston, and sympathy
walkouts by tens of thousands of miners at other companies idled
much of the nation's coal production in June and July.
   ``We're talking about communities being torn apart and in some
cases families torn apart,'' Mrs. Dole said after meeting with
company officials, strikers and workers hired to take their place
in the mines. ``It's time to start the healing process.''
   Union leader Trumka has asked repeatedly to meet with Douglas,
but Douglas has declined, saying local managers understood
conditions better than he.
   ``We have our best team at the bargaining table,'' said Michael
Odom, president of Pittston's Lebanon-based mining subsidiary. Odom
declined to comment on the meeting between Trumka and Douglas.
   Wages aren't an issue in the strike. The union wants a benefits
and job security package equal to the rest of the coal industry.
The company has declined, saying it needs more flexibility in its
work schedules and costs in order to compete with foreign mines.
   The strike has become a rallying point for organized labor
across the country. Union leaders contend the company is attempting
to break the UMW with the help of one-sided labor laws. Pittston
denies it is trying to rid itself of union employees.
   Mrs. Dole spoke to many of the 280 pickets at the entrance to a
mammoth coal preparation plant that 98 striking miners invaded and
occupied for four days in September.
   ``They're trying to destroy our union,'' Joel Phillips, a picket
captain from Castlewood, told her.
   Twelve miles away in Lebanon, one of seven Pittston Coal Group
employees Mrs. Dole talked to said he was attacked three times on
his way home from work in August after his truck tires were
flattened by twisted nails called jackrocks.
   With tears in his eyes and his hand in a cast, Roger Helbert of
Russell County said his nose was broken and his fingers crushed by
large rocks hurled through his car window and windshield.
   ``It was terrible,'' he said.
   An official of Poland's Solidarity union visited the coal fields
Wednesday and Thursday, met with Mrs. Dole Thursday and criticized
the treatment of striking miners.
   UMW spokesman Gene Carroll said he believed the labor
secretary's trip was made in part because the the Bush
administration was embarrassed that the Polish labor leader
complained about this country's treatment of workers.
   Mrs. Dole denied that, saying she came to Virginia because she
was frustrated at the long impasse and concerned about the
suffering of strikers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bloch-Prostitute     10-14 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch-Prostitute,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bloch Paid Vienna Prostitute Up to $10,000 a Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix Bloch, the former U.S. diplomat suspected
of spying, maintained a seven-year relationship with an Austrian
prostitute who said he asked to be humiliated and beaten, ABC News
reported.
   Bloch spent up to $10,000 a year on the prostitute, identified
only as ``Tina,'' and was her only customer for a year or two, ABC
News reported Friday.
   With the assistance of the Austrian government, the FBI brought
Tina to the United States in early August to be interrogated and to
testify before a secret grand jury, ABC reported, without saying
where the interview took place.
   Tina told ABC the grand jury wanted to know about Bloch's sexual
habits.
   ``I told them that he came to me once a week to be humiliated
and be beaten,'' she said, adding that Bloch never revealed any
secrets to her.
   Bloch, the former No. 2 official at the U.S. Embassy in Vienna
and a 30-year veteran of the Foreign Service, has been under
surveillance by FBI agents since June. He has not been charged with
any crime but was put on paid leave at the State Department in June.
   The Justice Department launched its probe after Bloch, 54, was
photographed handing a briefcase to a suspected Soviet agent in a
restaurant in Paris in May.
   The relationship between Bloch and Tina has increased concern
among U.S. officials that Bloch might have had fallen into a Soviet
sex trap, ABC said.
   Tina told ABC that Bloch would visit her once or twice a week
and pay $200 each time. Bloch was earning $60,000-$80,000 a year
during that period, ABC reported.
   She said she did not know at first that Bloch was a U.S.
diplomat but said he later complained about his job at the U.S.
mission in Vienna.
   ``You couldn't have a real conversation with him and you always
had the idea that he was depressed or down. You had the idea he was
very discontent with everything,'' Tina told ABC.
   Bloch, who was in West Virginia Friday, declined to comment to
ABC about the report.
   He did not return a message left by The Associated Press on his
home telephone answering machine, and his lawyer was not at home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
