<FIRST>u i PM-Market-World     10-14 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-World,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Europe, Asia Will Follow New York Plunge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Market Drop, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial analysts predicted global selling
following the New York stock market plunge but most said it would
not equal the 1987 crash. A Hong Kong securities director dismissed
the dip as a U.S. problem.
   The second-largest dive in U.S. history occurred mostly in the
final hour of trading in New York, after markets in Tokyo, London
and elsewhere had closed. But the fallout was expected to continue
Monday with the reopening of financial markets elsewhere.
   U.S. analysts blamed the 190.58 decline on collapse of the
``junk bond'' market _ which has been used to finance takeovers and
leveraged buyouts _ and an increase in the producer price index,
indicating higher inflation.
   The Times of London said today, ``World stock markets are
bracing themselves for a rerun of the 1987 crash. Fund managers
were forecasting that the fall would lead to a global wave of
selling, although many doubted that it would be at the panic levels
of 1987.''
   But in Hong Kong, Larry Tam, director of Sun Hung Kai
Securities, said the crash was a U.S. problem. He said it probably
would not greatly affect the Hong Kong stock market when it
reopened Monday, although the index might drop 50 to 60 points.
   He said the Hong Kong market had risen in past days because the
British colony was planning significant projects such as a new
airport. Hong Kong traders, therefore, were confident and probably
would not be affected, he said.
   In trading today, gold rose $3.71 an ounce on the Hong Kong
market, to close at $367.40, compared to Friday's close of $363.69.
   In Tokyo, Kazuhiro Nomura of New Japan Securities Co. said,
``The Nikkei index might plunge when the Tokyo market opens Monday,
because Japanese investors will be inclined to sell.''
   He said the Tokyo exchange might drop temporarily but in the
long run the fall in New York would not have a major impact on the
Tokyo market.
   ``Since there is no change in Japanese economic fundamentals,
the Tokyo market will not fall as sharply as in New York just
because of the plunge on Wall Street,'' Nomura said.
   In London, Alex Hammond-Chambers of the British fund management
company Ivory and Sime said: ``I imagine London will follow suit on
Monday ... We survived that one (the 1987 crash) and the markets
have since recovered.''
   Richard Jeffrey, director of economics at the London securities
company Hoare Govett, said comparisons with 1987 were unfair
because many companies were now valued at lower levels.
   But he said prices on the London stock market could fall heavily
when it reopens Monday. He predicted the Financial Times share
price index of 30 leading British companies, a major market
indicator, could fall to 1,718 Monday against 1,818 at close Friday.
   His predicted 100-point fall compares with a drop of 183.7
points on Oct. 19, 1987 _ the first day of the crash two years ago.
   Jeffrey said the London market had escaped the vogue for junk
bonds and would be cushioned from a dramatic collapse.
   The Bank of England in a statement late Friday also said the
U.S. market had been underpinned by leveraged transactions.
   But John Chiene, chairman of the British investment bank County
NatWest Wood Mackenzie, said, ``Our (London) stock market has been
in a delicate condition for some time. Given the extent to which we
have been tracking Wall Street, this news is likely to have a
significant adverse impact on Monday.''
   London stock market prices have been weak as the value of the
British pound continued to slip despite high interest rates.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government on
Oct. 5 increased British interest rates by one percentage point to
15 percent following rate increases by West Germany and five other
European countries.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed late Friday 39.8
points lower over the week.
   Terry Connor, from the London finance house Robert Fleming,
said, ``Sentiment in London was already nervous. It's reminiscent
of 1987 and almost anything can happen...
   ``Given the fear element and the closeness of the anniversary of
the 1987 crash, we are in for a very nervous Monday.''
</TEXT>
