<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany-Workers 1stLd-Writethru   10-14 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-Workers, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0430,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strained Work Force Further Taxed by Refugee Departures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS 5 grafs to reorganize; picks up 6th pvs, `Top-ranking
Communist...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany says the refugee
exodus has cut significantly into its labor force, and its
Communist government is calling on those left behind to help close
the gap.
   ``We certainly can do more, indeed a lot more,'' the state
newspaper Berliner Zeitung urged the country's workers Friday.
   Even before tens of thousands of people, many of them skilled
young workers, began fleeing to the West, the East Germany economy
was demanding the maximum from its already restive labor force.
   More than 90 percent of working-age women hold jobs.
Unemployment among able-bodied men is officially non-existent. The
country has a 44-hour work week, the longest in Europe.
   The result is an economy that's the envy of its Soviet bloc
neighbors, but also one with increasing problems.
   Top-ranking Communist Party members warned this week of the
growing possibility of labor strikes, which once were unthinkable
in the tightly controlled society.
   The official news agency ADN said Friday that the refugee exodus
had created a ``noticeable decrease of the labor force potential''
and that the current contingent of foreign workers won't be able to
compensate for the loss.
   It put at 85,000 the number of workers from Vietnam, Angola,
Cuba, North Korea, Mozambique and China, but some estimates say the
total is far higher.
   The East German leadership would like to hire 80,000 more
Chinese to fill vacancies, the Viennese daily newspaper Der
Standard said this week.
   About 50,000 East Germans have fled to West Germany since July.
At least 70,000 others have emigrated or refused to return after
being allowed to visit West Germany.
   To make up for the loss, the communist leadership in East Berlin
has increasingly been pressing those left behind to rally around
the socialist system that's also facing burgeoning political
opposition.
   ``Don't forget that there are still enough GDR (East German)
citizens to keep building up the country, and who have the will to
strengthen socialism in the GDR,'' Politburo member Kurt Hager told
West Germany's ZDF television on Thursday in an interview in Moscow.
   Others took up that same theme Friday.
   Besides urging workers to do more, the Berliner Zeitung called
for a ``better mood'' and greater efficiency on the job.
   Harry Tisch, a member of the ruling Politburo and head of the
government-run labor federation, said millions of people are still
``giving their best for socialism.''
   ``Now it's important to use to an even greater degree this
potential, power, readiness, richness of ideas and creativity,''
Tisch said in a commentary in the federation's daily newspaper,
Tribuene.
   As head of the Freie Deutsche Gewerkschaftsbund, Tisch oversees
the nation's work force of nearly 8.6 million people. Recent
estimates put the country's population at about 16.6 million,
before the refugee exodus.
   East German leader Erich Honecker sounded the same theme Friday,
saying: ``Our motto `work together, plan together, govern together'
is more current than ever.''
   His comments came in a meeting with leaders of political parties
allied with the Communists, held to discuss the recent troubles
that have hit the nation.
</TEXT>
