<DOCNO> AP891014-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0503EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     10-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Refugees Fast To Protest Repatriation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 11,000 Vietnamese boat people in
detention centers throughout this British colony today staged a
hunger strike to protest forced repatriation to their communist
homeland, officials reported.
   Nearly all the 7,000 inhabitants in the Shek Kong Detention
Center refused to have breakfast and lunch Saturday, said a police
spokesman on condition of anonymity. She added boat people hung
banners in the camp saying, ``Do not repatriate us to Vietnam.''
   A government spokesman said 4,100 boat people in detention
centers in Shatin and on Lantao Island also stopped eating.
   The actions came before meetings in Geneva Monday and Tuesday
that will review plans to screen Vietnamese boat people and
repatriate those who do not qualify as refugees.
   Under a policy adopted by Hong Kong and many Southeast Asian
nations in June 1988, Vietnamese boat people will be granted
refugee status and resettled overseas only if they can prove they
fled political persecution in Vietnam. Otherwise, they would be
considered illegal immigrants and face repatriation.
   The government spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said pamphlets had been found in some camps urging the boat people
to hold rallies and hunger strikes against the screening policy.
   He said there were no incidents of disorder and the hunger
strikers did not pose any security threat.
   More than 56,000 boat people are in Hong Kong. Two-thirds of
them are kept in the prison-like centers, waiting to be screened.
   In August, Vietnamese battled each other with iron bars, stones
and sharpened objects at one detention center. Seventeen people
were injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CannibalismConclusion 1stLd-Writethru a0414 10-14 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Conclusion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0414,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>He Killed His Fellow Man and Ate the Evidence, They Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf to chage 1974 to 1874; Alferd is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The verdict's in from experts who dug up the
common grave of five Colorado gold prospectors to see who did them
in and ate them up: Alferd Packer was the murderer with an appetite
for his victims.
   ``Guilty as sin,'' intoned James E. Starrs, a professor of law
and forensic science who led an expedition to Lake City, Colo., to
show what experts in archeology, anthropology, pathology and
firearms could learn about misdeeds committed 115 years ago.
   Starrs said Friday the bones provided scientific evidence that
prove Packer ``beyond the shadow of a doubt'' murdered his
colleagues, marooned in the Rocky Mountains during the murderous
winter of 1874, and ate their flesh to stay alive.
   It was a famous case of cannibalism, and the stuff of legends.
   Packer, accused of killing his fellow prospectors in 1874, was
convicted of murder in 1883 and of five charges of manslaughter
three years later when the first conviction was overturned on a
technicality.
   He owned up to surviving on the flesh of his fellow travelers,
but said the only one he actually killed was a hunger-crazed
Shannon Wilson Bell.
   He said Bell rushed him with a hatchet when he returned empty
handed from a five-day sortie in search for food. He said Bell had
killed the others and cannibalized them.
   He said he shot Bell in self-defense, finished him off with the
hatchet and then survived the winter through cannibalism.
   But the bones showed contradictory evidence, Starrs said.
   ``It is plain as a pikestaff that Packer was the one who was on
the attack, not Bell,'' he said, explaining that wounds on the
bones of three of the victims ``were caused by a hatchet-like
instrument at a time when these persons were defending themselves
from the attack of an aggressor.''
   He said the marks suggested the victims had raised their arms to
fend off blows.
   Starrs said the angle of the blade marks on the bones from which
the flesh had been taken _ including the bones believed to be
Bell's _ indicated that the cuts were all made by the same person.
That indicates Packer's story is false, and that he's guilty, he
said.
   However, Starrs acknowledged his findings had their limits. He
said, for example, he could not be sure which set of bones was
Bell's.
   Anthropologist Walter H. Birkby of the Arizona State Museum, who
also studied the bones, said he couldn't share Starrs' conclusions.
   ``It could possibly be the right scenario, but scientifically we
cannot substantiate it,'' Birkby said.
   Last summer Birkby went further, saying his study of the remains
actually supported Packer's story.
   No matter what his proclivities toward his fellow man, Packer
has been a fixture in Colorado folk history. His bust has been
displayed in the state capitol.
   Students at the University of Colorado at Boulder named their
student center dining room after Packer.
   Part of his fame comes from a remark Starrs said was never
uttered. Judge Melville Gerry, upon sentencing Packer, supposedly
declared, ``They was sivin Dimmicrats in Hinsdale County, and ye
eat five of them, God damn ye!''
   Starrs said he believes the quotation was made up by a bartender.
   Starrs also came to one conclusion not far off the opinion many
people held in the last century: Packer was a fiend, ``base ...
brutish ... barbaric,'' he said.
   One remaining mystery was cleared up when Duane J. Dillon, a
criminal investigator from Martinez, Calif., concluded Packer
spelled his first name ``A-l-f-e-r-d.''
   He said official records show the name as ``Alfred,'' but
whenever Packer signed a document he used ``Alferd.''
</TEXT>
