<FIRST>r a PM-Series-Fans     10-14 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Series-Fans,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fans On Both Sides Of Bay Rally For Home Teams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball fever was in full swing on the eve
of the Bay Bridge World Series as thousands of fans turned out at
dueling rallies to urge on the San Francisco Giants and the Oakland
Athletics.
   At least 15,000 Giants fans jammed into a waterfront plaza in
San Francisco at midday Friday, while some 2,000 A's boosters
turned up later at the Oakland Coliseum plaza.
   Shouts of ``Lets Go, A's'' greeted Manager Tony La Russa,
pitcher Dave Stewart and reliever Dennis Eckersley. They promised
that the American League champions, who lost last year's World
Series 4-1 to the Los Angeles Dodgers, would win this time.
   ``Last year I made a big mistake in the Series,'' said
Eckersley, who gave up a game-losing, two-run homer to Kirk Gibson
with two out in the ninth inning of Game 1. ``And this year I will
redeem myself.''
   La Russa told the crowd it wasn't enough to merely get into the
Series.
   ``We're only going to be happy if we win it,'' the skipper said.
   Across the bay, Giants fans listened to a Dixieland band that
played on a stand decorated with balloons in the team's hues of
orange and black.
   ``They can't stop the black tide,'' Giants pitcher Mike Krukow
told the crowd.
   Fans greeted Krukow, the only member of the team to address the
noon rally, with shouts of ``Kru, Kru, Kru.'' The pitcher finished
the season on the injured list and won't play in the Series.
   The rally also was intended to boost prospects for the proposed
waterfront stadium that would become the team's new home, replacing
windy Candlestick Park.
   Several desks staffed by supporters of the ballpark plan dotted
the area. Fans were urged to sign up as volunteers in a campaign to
get the stadium plan approved on the November ballot.
   ``This is tremendous; people are really getting the spirit,''
said Marge Savo, who wore a Giants cap, team sweater and black
skirt as she sat at one of the desks.
</TEXT>
