<FIRST>r i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0462 10-14 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanian Minister Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Miranda was...' to restore dropped first name
of justice minister; Pickup 5th pvs, `Renato Pereira...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The justice minister resigned, citing
deterioration of his health and neglect of his ranch during the six
weeks he held office. An adviser to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega was
named to replace him.
   A journalist for the Madrid newspaper El Pais took refuge in the
Spanish Embassy Friday, saying he had been threatened with arrest.
   The opposition indicated Friday it would discuss conditions for
new elections.
   Olmedo Miranda was appointed Sept. 3, two days after provisional
President Francisco Rodriguez took office. The provisional
government was created when Noriega annulled the May 7 elections,
which independent observers said the opposition won by a landslide.
   Renato Pereira, a foreign relations expert and adviser to
Noriega, was appointed to replace Miranda after Miranda's
resignation Friday.
   In his resignation letter to Rodriguez, Miranda said: ``I have
faced mainly damage to my health (while in office), and in
addition, I have neglected the duties of my cattle business.''
   His resignation followed government announcements that one-third
of the 140,000 public employees could be fired over the next weeks
under tough new laws against workers deemed disloyal to the
government.
   Many public employees celebrated Oct. 3, when rebellious
military units tried to overthrow Noriega, who as chief of the
Defense Forces controls the country.
   The new measures make it easy for the government to dismiss such
employees. The laws also freeze wages, suspend Christmas bonuses
and forbid any political activity by professional and business
associations.
   The government said the laws were enacted to defend the economy
against ``aggression by the United States.''
   Since Noriega's indictment in February 1988 on U.S. drug
trafficking charges, the United States has applied economic and
political pressure to force the Defense Forces chief to step down.
   Noriega denies the drug charges and says the United States is
trying to avoid complying with the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties,
which give Panama control of the waterway at the end of 1999.
   The Spanish journalist, Antonio Cano, said officials called him
at his hotel, criticized a story he had written about Noriega and
threatened him with arrest. He said he wrote a profile with
references to Noriega's personal life.
   Cano, 32, lives in Mexico and has covered Panama since 1984. He
arrived last week to report on the military uprising.
   Government officials were not available for comment on the
reported threats.
   Cano said he called Spanish officials, who took him to the
embassy for protection and were looking for ways to get him out of
the country.
   Former presidential candidate Guillermo Endara said the
opposition was willing to talk with the military about ``another
kind of elections'' but would continue to insist on Noriega's
departure and recognition of its May victory.
   International observers said Endara beat the government
candidate by a 3-1 margin.
   ``We would be willing to hold talks on many grounds,'' Endara
said. ``If Gen. Noriega is willing to leave, we would be willing to
consider what kind of elections could be held.''
</TEXT>
