<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MarcosMass     10-14 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Mass,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Funeral Mass Said in Honolulu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,500 people crowded into a sweltering
church to hear former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
eulogized as a man who suffered like Jesus Christ and forgave those
who betrayed him.
   Another 500 people milled outside the Co-Cathedral of St.
Theresa Friday, hoping for a glimpse of Marcos' body Friday evening.
   ``Christ was a victim of the people's power, so Marcos was a
victim of the peoples' power,'' said Roman Catholic Monsignor
Domingo Nebres of the Philippines, referring to the 1986 ``people
power'' revolt that ended Marcos' 20-year dictatorial rule there.
   ``My dear beloved president would say, `Do not cry for me ...
cry for your country,'' Nebres, a friend of Marcos for 12 years,
told those packed into the Honolulu's largest Roman Catholic church.
   After the Mass, Nebres told reporters, ``We cannot imitate
Christ in power, he is God. We can only imitate him in suffering,
which Marcos did.''
   Marcos was hospitalized for nearly nine months before he died
Sept. 28 at the age of 72.
   Last year, he was indicted on U.S. criminal racketeering charges
accusing him of looting millions of dollars from his homeland.
   In exile, he was accused of plotting to overthrow Philippine
President Corazon Aquino, who prohibited him from returning to his
homeland.
   But his widow, Imelda, who still faces the racketeering charges,
has vowed to bring his body home to the Philippines for burial. He
will be entombed Sunday at Valley of the Temples Memorial Park in
what the family calls a temporary resting place.
   Despite being rejected by his people, Marcos was never bitter,
Nebres said. ``He would say `Lord, forgive them, they know not what
they do,''' said the priest, who regularly heard Marcos'
confessions.
   Marcos' coffin, draped with a Philippine flag, was carried into
the church by 10 men in white Philippine military uniforms and
black armbands. Eight were retired generals.
   The procession was led by Col. Arturo Aruiza, a 20-year Marcos
aide and his closest adviser-in-exile.
   Mrs. Marcos arrived with two of her three children, Ferdinand
``Bong Bong'' Marcos Jr. and daughter Irene Araneta, as well as
other relatives including Marcos' sister, Fortuna Barba, and
brother, Pacifico Marcos.
   Marcos eldest daughter, Imee, lives in exile in Morocco.
   The black-clad Mrs. Marcos, who covered her face with a black
veil and clutched a silver rosary, refused to answer reporters'
questions.
   During the service, a tearful Aruiza stood guard near Marcos'
closed coffin, which was surrounded by white flowers and red velvet
ropes to keep mourners from getting too close.
   After the hour-long Mass, the coffin was opened, Mrs. Marcos
kissed the clear plastic covering it and placed a single white lily
there.
   Throngs of mourners, including hundreds who pushed their way
into the church after rain began to fall at the end of the Mass,
filed past the coffin.
   Philippine Consul General to Hawaii Tomas Gomez said there were
no official representatives of the Philippine or U.S. governments
at the funeral.
   However, several Philippine officials attended, including former
Labor Minister Blas Ople and Congressman Roquito Ablan Jr., said
Marcos supporter Joe Lazo.
   Also attending were Eduardo Cojuangco Jr.; Christina Ponce
Enrile, wife of Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, the former defense
minister; and the wife of Philippine Gen. Fabian Ver, Marcos'
right-hand man during his rule.
   Cojuangco is Mrs. Aquino's cousin, but a longtime Marcos
supporter.
</TEXT>
