<DOCNO> AP891014-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0603EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Pope     10-14 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Arrives At Indian Ocean Island on Final Leg of Eastern Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAISANCE, Mauritius (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul ll arrived today for
a two-day stay in this multiparty democracy in which a rainbow of
races and religions co-exist peacefully.
   The Roman Catholic leader landed in cloudy, windy weather on
this volcanic, Indian Ocean island after a 7{-hour flight from
Jakarta, Indonesia.
   Prime Minister Anerood Jugnauth greeted the pope with Hindu,
Christian and Moslem members of his government.
   John Paul's weekend stop follows a politically sensitive Asian
pilgrimage in which he was called to speak out on human rights
issues in South Korea and Indonesia.
   On Sunday, John Paul will visit the 50-square-mile island of
Rodrigues, 500 miles to the east, before returning to Rome Monday.
   At his final stops on his tour of Indonesia on Friday, John Paul
stressed the Catholic Church's family and social teachings while
acknowledging difficulties faced by Indonesia's Christians.
   He continued to use guarded language when referring to potential
controversial issues involving the government or the 157
million-member Moslem community in the world's most populous Moslem
country.
   His final Indonesian Mass was attended by 100,000 people Friday
amid lush coffee and palm oil plantations in North Sumatra. Later
he addressed Indonesia's 42 bishops in Jakarta, the capital.
   John Paul urged Catholics to be bold in proclaiming Christian
values. He acknowledged ``occasional difficulties'' facing the 5
million Catholics in Indonesia but reminded them religious freedom
is protected by Indonesia's constitution.
   In Mauritius, Hindus account for just over half of its 1 million
people. About 320,000 are Catholics and 16 percent are Moslems.
Hindus and Moslems emigrated from India in the 19th century to
Mauritius, 1,000 miles east of the African mainland.
   Catholicism was brought by the French when they settled in 1721.
The British gained control and granted Mauritius independence in
1968.
   It has a multiparty parliamentary democracy, a free press and a
commitment to separation of religion and state.
   Cardinal Jean Margeot, head of the nation's Catholics, addressed
a letter to all Mauritians asking them to welcome the pope ``as a
pilgrim of peace.''
   ``May each of the different groups of our society keep its own
identity, like the colors of the rainbow, and seek elevation
mutually,'' said Margeot.
   ``Unity in diversity,'' is the motto of the prime minister, Sir
Anerood Jugnauth, 59, a Hindu who has five Catholics in his Cabinet
and a picture of the pope on his office wall.
   However, Hindus twice tried to assassinate Jugnauth after he
launched a crackdown against the drug trade last year.
   But Margeot said he will have good news for the pope about
Mauritius, which has almost full employment and a real growth rate
that has averaged 7 percent in recent years.
   ``We are changing from a rural economy based on agriculture to
accelerated industrialization,'' the cardinal said.
   Most of the population are Creoles, whose skin color ranges from
fairest white to darkest black, with racial features of Europeans,
Africans and Indians, and a touch of Chinese. All the ethnic
variety of the Indian subcontinent is also represented.
   Mauritius is considered a shining example of peaceful
coexistence. American novelist Mark Twain once described it as the
model for paradise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-14 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSSINING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of pledges had a run of baa-ad
luck when they followed the advice of fraternity members to say
only ``Sheep run north, sir'' after being abandoned in this New
York City suburb.
   Twenty Pace University students were charged with disorderly
conduct early Friday after the wild and woolly fraternity prank in
which they answered all questions from police with just that
phrase, authorities said.
   The incident began around midnight when brothers of Delta Kappa
Epsilon drove their blindfolded pledges up near the Croton Dam and
dropped them off with no identification and no money, police said.
   They did give the pledges some advice _ if anyone asks you
anything, reply, ``Sheep run north, sir.'' The pledges responded
like, well, sheep.
   The pledges were walking back to school when Officer Richard
Garrett spotted them along a highway and decided to investigate.
   Garrett asked for identification. ``Sheep run north, sir!'' they
replied.
   He asked what they were doing on the highway at 2 a.m. ``Sheep
run north, sir!'' they replied.
   He called for reinforcements and arrested them all. ``Sheep run
north, sir!'' they told the arriving officers.
   The police began strip-searching everybody and locking them in
cells. ``We're college students!'' they responded _ but only after
a half-dozen were already behind bars.
   They were given disorderly conduct tickets, and released in the
custody of Pace's assistant dean of students, Robert Haywood.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bloomfield, Iowa, needs another signature in
the guest book at its Welcome Center, but not from just anyone.
   To make sure it gets a name from the only state not represented
in the book, the town is sponsoring a Delaware contest. The prize
is an all-expense paid, three-day trip for two to Bloomfield _
population 2,700.
   And, oh, what a weekend it will be. The winners will stay at
Motel 63, tool around in a donated car with $15 free gas, $50 of
gift certicates and receive free newspapers while they are there.
   To win the trip and goodies, Delaware residents must submit an
essay of 50 words or less to the Davis County Tourism Corp. on
``Why I would like to visit Davis County, Iowa.''
   Nancy Schneider, president of the 3-year-old non-profit tourism
corporation, said she received a call Friday morning from a man in
Delaware who said he plans to be the first to sign the book because
he'll be in Iowa next week.
   ``He was told that in order to get the royal treatment, he'll
have to enter the contest,'' Schneider said in a telephone
interview.
   According to the guest book, people from 49 states, about 35
countries and all of the Canadian provinces have visited
Bloomfield, about 75 miles southeast of Des Moines.
</TEXT>
