<FIRST>r a PM-SternSonDebut     10-14 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stern Son Debut,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son Of Famed Violinist Follows Brother Into Conducting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't in the original score, but the
youngest son of renowned violinst Isaac Stern is following in the
footsteps of his older brother and taking up the baton as a career.
   David Stern, 26, who graduated this year from the Juilliard
School in New York City, will make his conducting debut today with
the Yale Symphony Orchestra. The orchestra will perform Schubert's
Symphony No. 8 and Shostakovich's Symphony No. 5.
   Stern, a pianist, was asked to take over as interim music
director for a year after the abrupt departure of Alasdair Neale,
who left last spring to become assistant conductor of the San
Francisco Symphony Orchestra.
   To keep the job with the undergraduate orchestra, Stern will
have to compete with other candidates in auditions next year.
   A 1986 graduate of Yale, Stern called the position a ``great,
great job'' for a young conductor. Past directors have gone on to
work with well known orchestras, but Stern said he's concentrating
strictly on his present job.
   ``This is an orchestra that judges it conductors very severely.
They demand quality and the demand attention, and they demand
seriousness. I am trying to earn my keep not only with my superiors
to which I answer but also to the orchestra,'' he said.
   Neither David nor his brother, Michael, 29, who is assistant
conductor of the Cleveland Orchestra, were encouraged by their
father to think of music as a career, David said. Their sister,
Shira, 33, is a rabbi.
   ``My father did not push us into music,'' he said. ``The love
for music was something that was ingrained in us when we were very
young, and I think he was very happy when we chose it. But we chose
it very late.''
   David learned the piano at an early age. In high school, he said
he intended to focus on science, but ``somehow I got involved in
the music department and getting more and more involved in music.''
   He played in a jazz band and also performed chamber music. But
when he started college, he still wasn't thinking of a career in
music.
   As a freshman, Stern was an assistant to the director of the
Bach Society Orchestra and Chorus, an undergraduate organization
run by students. When the director quit during his sophomore year,
he took over, and the course was set.
   He enrolled in the Yale School of Music for conducting studies
under Otto-Werner Mueller, and then followed Mueller to New York
when he joined the Juilliard faculty.
   Stern says his father's status has posed some challenges. He
said he has been offered some positions, such as assistantships,
which have been ``ridiculously out of proportion.''
   ``I have had to say, `I'm sorry, I'm not ready for this,''' he
said.
</TEXT>
