<HEAD>Young To Take Consulting Job After Leaving Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Andrew Young has agreed to take a
consulting job with a political supporter when his term expires at
the end of the year.
   The arrangement will allow Young to spend most of his time in
1990 campaigning for governor, said Stoney Cooks, a supporter.
   The mayor has been hired as a consultant for R.K. Sehgal,
chairman of the engineering firm Law Companies Group and a backer
of the mayor's gubernatorial campaign, Nehl Horton, a campaign
aide, said Friday.
   The salary was not disclosed. Young earns $65,000 a year as
mayor.
   Young will serve as an executive consultant for a Law
subsidiary, Law International Companies Group, lending the firm his
extensive international experience. Young served as ambassador to
the United Nations under President Carter.
   Law recently merged with a British firm to increase its overseas
business. The firm has 3,400 employees worldwide, including Africa
and the Middle East.
   Should Young be elected governor in November 1990, his agreement
with Law would end. He has not formally announced his candidacy yet.
   City and company officials said Law has no contracts with the
city.
