<FIRST>r a PM-ShipSurvivors     10-14 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Survivors,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Men Survive 40 Hours in Pacific After Boat Sinks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HU1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six men survived 40 hours in the Pacific Ocean
by fashioning a makeshift raft out of buoys and nets from their
sunken fishing boat, the Coast Guard said.
   The Coast Guard cutter Washington rescued the men Friday after a
helicopter spotted them bobbing 50 miles northwest of Maui Island,
spokesman Lt. Brad Nelson said.
   The men suffered only bruises and mild dehydration, Nelson said.
   ``They were all in the water, clinging to the raft,'' said
helicopter pilot Lt. Michael Andres, who first spotted the men.
``They were waving and giving us the thumbs-up sign and we motioned
back to them to tell them that the cutter was on the way.''
   The Coast Guard identified the sailors as skipper Kim H. Kyu,
49; Jim Alexander, 22; George Shohswel, 22; Chong S. Yoon, 39; Osa
A. Tui, 42, and John Aignua, 39.
   They were greeted by relatives and friends with hugs and tears
when the Washington returned them to Honolulu Harbor. The men
declined to be interviewed.
   The Coast Guard and Navy searched 70,000 square miles for the
men after the 60-foot long-line fishing boat Sin Hyung radioed it
was taking on water and breaking up Wednesday evening.
   The Sin Hyung sailed from Honolulu on Oct. 3.
   Lt. Dan Nelson, skipper of the Washington, said the fishing boat
carried no flares or emergency radio transmitters and apparently
had no life jackets.
   ``They were real smart to use those buoys,'' Andres said. ``But
we would have found them a lot sooner if they had flares or an
emergency beacon.''
</TEXT>
