<HEAD>Racers Collided With Friday the 13th, Publicist Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLEJO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of competitors in the Great Race
West, a classic car competition, ran head-on into Friday the 13th,
a publicist for the event said.
   David and Laura Northrop of Redlands, Calif., driving car number
13, a 1930 Ford Phaeton, crossed the day's finish line in 13th
place, said Phil Cole, publicist for the 1,000-mile road rally
between Long Beach and Sparks, Nev.
   They also began the day's rally in 13th place, he said.
   And when they finished, their speedometer was stuck _ you
guessed it _ at the 13 mph mark.
   ``I swear that this happened,'' said Cole. ``If I hadn't seen it
myself, I wouldn't have believed it.''
   He said the Northrops made no attempt during the 325-mile leg
from Avila Beach to Vallejo to maintain their race position.
   ``They are pretty good racers,'' he said. ``They would much
rather win.''
   The rally is scheduled to end Sunday.
