<FIRST>r i PM-Sony-Warner     10-14 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sony-Warner,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Sues Warner Bros. in Bid to Hire Producers of ``Batman'' and
``Rainman''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. said today that it has filed a $100
million suit against Warner Bros. Inc., the latest salvo in the
electronics giant's bid to hire a pair of famous film producers to
head its new movie company.
   The suit follows a $1 billion lawsuit filed by earlier by Warner
Bros., which wants to keep Sony from hiring producers Peter Guber
and Jon Peters. The two men made the hit movie ``Batman'' for
Warner Bros. and have a long-term production deal with the company.
   Sony USA Inc., Guber and Peters and their production companies
jointly filed the lawsuit against Warner Bros. in California
Superior Court in Los Angeles on Friday, Sony Corp. said in a
statement.
   Sony, the Japanese electronics and record giant, announced Sept.
27 that it had agreed to buy Columbia Pictures for about $3.4
billion.
   The company said it intends to name Guber and Peters co-chairmen
of the company once it is acquired. Sony also has begun a tender
offer to buy The Guber-Peters Entertainment Co. for $200 million.
   Warner Bros. sued Sony and others for $1 billion in damages over
Sony's courtship of Guber and Peters to run Columbia Pictures
Entertainment Inc.
   ``Our suit is against Warner Bros., Inc., Steven Ross, chairman
of its parent company Warner Communications Co., Terry Semel and
Robert Daly for their violation of contracts, illegal conduct and
unfair competition,'' said a Sony official in Tokyo who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Our company had been negotiating with Warner Bros. Inc. in an
attempt to reach agreement ... and it is very regretful that Warner
Bros. filed a suit against us,'' he said.
   But he said the two sides would continue attempts to reach an
agreement regardless of the lawsuits.
   ``We are confident that Warner cannot stop the two (Guber and
Peters) from becoming involved in management of Columbia Pictures,
and we strongly believe that the court will be on our side,'' said
the statement from Sony's Tokyo headquarters.
   Warner Bros. said Guber and Peters, who also produced the
Oscar-winning ``Rainman,'' recently signed a five-year agreement to
make films for Warner.
   In its suit, Warner accused Sony of inducing the two executives
to breach their agreement so they could take top jobs at Columbia.
</TEXT>
