<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Fire     10-14 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Fire,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arsonists Kill Seven Children, Five Others in Eviction Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arsonists seeking to evict squatters
from a shantytown on the outskirts of the capital set fires that
killed at least 12 people and left 2,000 homeless, police said
today.
   About 30 people were injured in Friday's blazes, according to
hospital sources who spoke on condition of anonymity. The fires
destroyed about 300 mud-and-straw huts, most of which were built in
the past five months by poor people who had been evicted from
similar shantytowns in the heart of Dhaka.
   ``The arsonists held a meeting before dousing the huts with
gasoline and kerosene. They also exploded some firebombs to keep
the slum people inside their huts,'' a police officer at Mirpur
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said two firemen were beaten by ``miscreants'' who blocked
their efforts to control the fire.
   Most of those who died were trapped in their burning huts. Seven
children were among the dead.
   The death toll initially was put at eight, but more bodies were
discovered overnight and after daybreak.
   Police detained 20 people on arson charges and said they were
looking for more. Interior Minister Mahmudul Hasan, who visited the
Kalayyanpur slum late Friday night, ordered ``stern action''
against the arsonists.
   About 200 people, many of them students from a nearby college
and school, were involved in setting the fire and were supported by
local strongmen, police said. Both residents and police said the
institutions were claiming the land.
   The police officer at Mirpur, which is just north of Dhaka, said
the shantytown residents were evicted from a slum in central Dhaka
about five months ago as part of a city beautification campaign.
   Almost one-third of Dhaka's 6 million people live in slums and
shantytowns.
</TEXT>
