<HEAD>Married Couple New Co-Editors At U.S. News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A husband-wife team is taking over as
co-editors of U.S. News &amp; World Report, says a spokeswoman for the
magazine.
   Michael Ruby and Merrill McLoughlin will assume the post Oct.
23, replacing Roger Rosenblatt, who resigned on Thursday night,
Kathy Bushkin said Friday.
   Before their promotions, Ms. McLoughlin, 44, was a senior editor
at the magazine and Ruby, 47, was executive editor.
   Ms. Bushkin said Rosenblatt is resigning because the commute
between the magazine's headquarters in Washington and his home in
New York was disrupting his family life.
   However, The Washington Post reported in today's editions that
Rosenblatt was quitting because of a conflict with the magazine's
publisher, Mortimer Zuckerman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bolar's Nitrofurantoin Targeted by FDA</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration says it wants
to withdraw Bolar Pharmaceutical Co.'s approval to sell a generic
drug used to treat urinary tract infections and it wants the
company to withdraw the product from drugstores.
   In a letter to the company, the FDA said tests on samples of
Bolar's drug and the brand-name drug ``strongly suggest that
Norwich-Eaton's Macrodantin product was substituted for Bolar's
product'' in tests required for FDA approval.
   The FDA is also moving to change its listing of Bolar's version
of Macrodantin, generically called nitrofurantoin, to indicate to
physicians that the agency does not consider the product to be
therapeutically equivalent to the brand-name drug.
   At the FDA's request, Bolar last weekend agreed to recall its
nitrofurantoin from wholesalers. However, the FDA said it planned
to recommend legal action to force the company to withdraw the
product from pharmacy shelves as well.
   Officials of the Copiague, N.Y.-based company could not be
reached for comment.
   The FDA is investigating other product-switching allegations
against Bolar, including one involving the company's version of the
high-blood-pressure drug Dyazide. A federal criminal investigation
is also under way into the matter.
   The FDA does not have the authority to remove a drug from the
market. If a company does not comply with a recall request, the
agency can only force a recall in court.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Thornburgh Taking Six-Day Trip To Soviet Union</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh was scheduled
to depart on a six-day trip to the Soviet Union today to discuss
crime fighting tactics with Soviet officials and the American legal
system with law students.
   The trip by Thornburgh and a group of aides is being billed as
the first official visit to the Soviet Union.
   The attorney general said his discussions with Soviet legal
authorities would include ``joint law enforcement concerns in the
fields of drugs and organized crime.''
   ``It is my hope that through this visit we can establish a
continuing dialogue between U.S. and Soviet legal officials on
matters of common concern and interest,'' Thornburgh said in a
statement issued Friday.
   ``We have been asked to discuss with Soviet officials such
issues as human rights, the role of the judiciary and commercial
and regulatory law, including environmental law,'' said Thornburgh.
   The attorney general also plans to meet at the U.S. Embassy with
Soviet dissidents and human rights activists, said spokesman David
Runkel.
   Soviet emigration is also expected to be a topic of discussion
between Thornburgh and Soviet officials. The department has
expressed a desire to move the processing of Soviet refugees by
Immigration and Naturalization Ser vice officials from Rome to
Moscow.
</TEXT>
