<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0434 10-14 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede BERLIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poland Says East Germany Agrees To Let Refugees Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with East Germany agreeing to allow
more refugees leave Poland, edits to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany has agreed to allow almost
1,000 of its citizens who have taken refuge in Poland to emigrate
to the country of their choice, Poland said today.
   The state news agency PAP said East German Deputy Foreign
Minister Harry Ott met with Polish officials and worked out the
solution to the refugee problem.
   The refugees, including many families with small children, had
made their way to Poland after more than 1,400 East Germans left
for the West on Oct. 1 and Oct. 5.
   The exodus from Poland was part of a larger flood of East German
refugees fleeing West through Hungary and Czechoslovakia. The
deluge of an estimated 50,000 refugees since July has shaken East
Germany's hard-line government.
   Diplomatic sources today put the number of refugees in the West
German Embassy or at shelters in Poland at more than 950.
   The earlier groups of refugees left by special East German
trains sent to Poland. The PAP announcement said that this time,
the refugees would be allowed to go to any country they choose
after obtaining proper documents from the East German Embassy.
   It was unclear if the arrangement would apply to other East
Germans who make their way to Poland. Despite East Germany's
attempts to limit travel to Poland, an average of about 120
refugees a day have been arriving at the Warsaw embassy.
   Although Poland maintains it is trying to prevent illegal border
crossings from East Germany, it does not check the documents of
those who make it into Poland. Polish officials have been working
privately with the Roman Catholic Church and the Red Cross to
provide comfortable housing for the refugees.
   The East German ambassador to Poland visited the West German
Embassy just before the announcement on PAP, diplomatic sources
said.
   A group of about 40 East German refugees who apparently had just
arrived were seen today carrying their belongings out of the West
German Embassy and boarding a chartered city bus to a temporary
shelter in Konstancin, about 12 miles from Warsaw.
   ``Everything is O.K.,'' a West German Red Cross official told
the group. ``Don't be afraid,'' another refugee said to his
countrymen as they walked to the bus.
   Inside the embassy, another group of refugees appeared to be
preparing to depart in another waiting bus.
   It was not clear when the refugees would leave for the West.
West Germany's ZDF television network reported from Warsaw that
buses had been arranged but no firm plans had been announced.
   East Germany conceded Friday that the exodus of more than
100,000 of its young and skilled citizens in the past year has cut
significantly into its labor force, and it called on those who have
stayed behind to close the gap.
   ``We certainly can do more, indeed a lot more,'' the state
newspaper Berliner Zeitung urged the country's workers.
   In East Berlin Friday, the state news agency ADN announced that
all but 11 of the estimated 1,000 protesters who were jailed after
pro-democracy demonstrations last week and on Monday had been
released.
   Also Friday, a high-ranking East German official, Dietmar
Keller, spoke openly when asked about speculation of a possible
resignation of hard-line leader Erich Honecker, 77.
   ``As for Erich Honecker's resignation, Erich Honecker must make
that decision all alone,'' Keller, the No. 2 official in the
Culture Ministry, told a news conference in Wolfenbuettel, West
Germany.
   Keller added that any decision about Honecker's political fate
would require a meeting of the Central Committee.
   ``I don't know if a meeting is planned or already called,'' he
said.
   ``But if the majority of the Central Committee is of the opinion
that major changes are necessary, which is absolutely normal in the
world and in politics, then the required decision will be reached.''
   East German officials usually dismiss all questions about the
possibility Honecker could step down or be removed as
``provocative,'' in contrast to Keller's polite explanation of
procedures needed to make a change at the top.
   Honecker's unyielding course has come under increasing criticism
at home.
   Tens of thousands of East Germans took to the streets in
pro-democracy protests during and after the nation's 40th
anniversary celebrations last week. The demonstrators insist they
are staying in East Germany to seek democratic and economic reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
