<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     10-14 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Legislators Debate Syrian Presence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese legislators wrangled today
over a peace plan for their war-plagued country and appeared unable
to agree on ending Syria's military presence in their country.
   Conference sources said the legislators, meeting since Sept. 30,
narrowed their problems to the Syrian issue after a 17-member
parliamentary task force approved an amended draft for political
reforms during an all-night session.
   Michel Sassin, an Orthodox Christian deputy who is a member of
the committee, said the debates have ``reached an advanced stage in
the ... inter-Lebanese conciliation.'' He would not elaborate.
   The tentative approval of the first chapter of the Arab
League-proposed Lebanon peace plan drew ``cautious optimism'' from
the participants, the sources said, noting that deputies had
reneged on several previous accords after contacts with warlords
and militia chieftains in Beirut.
   The Lebanese civil war, which has raged for 14 years, has eroded
government authority and allowed militia factions to take control
of the streets. Consent of these factions is necessary for the
success of any accord that may be reached in Taif.
   One source said: ``They reach a consensus and then get a
telephone call from Beirut, and we are back where we started.''
   The sources, all of whom spoke on condition of anonymity,
explained that the second chapter of the peace plan _ which deals
with the necessity of an Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon _ had been
approved by all the participants without exception.
   But the deputies remained divided over the third and fourth
chapters of the plan _ ``Lebanese sovereignty'' and relations with
Syria. The plan was proposed by an Arab committee comprised of
Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria.
   The Christians are demanding written guarantees for a total
Syrian withdrawal from Lebanon. The Moslems have approved a phased
pullback from the Beirut area to be completed in two years,
followed by an evacuation after the conclusion of a Syrian-Lebanese
peace pact.
   A hard-line Christian deputy, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said a political reforms accord ``would be ink on
paper'' if no satisfactory solution is reached on the issue of
sovereignty and a timetable for the withdrawal of foreign forces.
   Syria has 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Once the committee completes its debates the draft four-chapter
plan would be submitted to a plenary session for approval.
Parliament then will take the document back to Beirut for
ratification at a session to be held in the Lebanese capital.
   The reforms envisaged by the Arab committee are designed to
redistribute power betwen Christians and Moslems and prepare for
the later stage of abolishing the sectarian system, in force since
independence from France in 1943.
   Christians then were considered the majority and given the upper
hand in the government, Parliament, army and judiciary. Moslems now
are believed to comprise a majority of Lebanon's estimated 4
million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
