<FIRST>u i PM-Syria-Defector     10-14 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Syria-Defector,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Damascus Admits Syrian Pilot Defected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria admitted today that an air force
pilot who landed his Soviet-built MiG-23 fighter jet in Israel this
week was a defector, and branded him ``an abominable traitor and an
Israeli spy.''
   Syria earlier had claimed that Maj. Mohammed Bassam Adel was
forced to land in northern Israel on Wednesday because of a
technical problem. Today, a military spokesman said the officer had
misled Syrian observation posts.
   ``He maneuvered in a way to indicate that his plane was facing
technical troubles,'' the unnamed spokesman told the official
Syrian Arab News Agency, SANA.
   ``Then he changed course and headed toward the occupied
territories to land in the Israeli Megiddo airport, selling himself
and his aircraft to the enemy,'' the spokesman said.
   On Wednesday, an official source said Adel's plane landed in
Israel with smoke pouring out of its engine. Damascus later
requested the assistance of the International Red Cross in
obtaining the repatriation of both the pilot and the plane.
   Adel, 34, told a news conference in Israel on Friday that he
defected in search of freedom and democracy and that he would not
meet with any Red Cross representatives if their aim is to take him
back to Syria.
   He was on a training mission near Syria's southern border when
he veered off and flew low toward northern Israel at 700-750 mph.
   SANA quoted the military spokesman as saying Adel's defection
``ended an espionage affair organized by the Israeli intelligence
service which had recruited this agent and used him to smuggle one
of our air force jets and deliver it to the enemy.''
   ``This abominable traitor and Israeli spy has stepped on all
sacred, national values when he sold his country and his people and
spied for the enemy ... He betrayed the honor and confidence of the
military,'' the spokesman added.
</TEXT>
