<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   10-14 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0495,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Travels to Poland Nov. 9; To Offer Debt-Relief, Mend Fences</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Kohl's chief...' to CORRECT second spelling
of Teltschik; picks up 8th graf: Klein said ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-East Germany, Bjt ^By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said his talks
next month with Poland's Solidarity-led government will be a
``historic chance'' to mend fences with a World War II adversary.
   Government spokesman Hans Klein said Kohl will offer Poland
relief for its $39 billion foreign debt during his Nov. 9-14 visit.
   Kohl's office also announced Friday that the chancellor will
visit Hungary soon, although no date has been set.
   West Germany has led efforts among European Community and
Western creditors to help Poland resolve its staggering economic
problems. The Bonn government has also been outspoken in its
support of democratic reforms instituted there and in Hungary.
   West Germany is Poland's biggest trading partner and its biggest
creditor, holding about 20 percent of Warsaw's foreign debt.
   ``We now have the historic chance, because of the dramatic
changes and improvements in Poland, for a new beginning in our
relations 50 years after World War II,'' Kohl told ARD television.
``We owe it to the younger generations to foster good
neighborliness and friendship.''
   Kohl's chief foreign affairs adviser, Horst Teltschik, and
Teltschik's Polish counterpart, Mieczyslaw Pszon, last week
concluded a package of financial and political accords that resolve
outstanding problems between the two countries, government
officials said.
   Klein said West Germany will tie its financial assistance to
specific projects. He confirmed the two governments have discussed
from $1 billion to $1.5 billion in aid.
   West Germany announced Monday that it had agreed to reschedule
$1.3 billion in Polish debt, and an earlier agreement effectively
wiped out about $523 million in loans to Poland.
   Among the accords are programs to improve living conditions for
ethnic Germans in Poland. The language and culture of the ethnic
minority have been discouraged in areas that were part of Germany
prior to World War II.
   West German officials concede privately that funds for
German-language schools and projects to increase production of
consumer goods are aimed partly at stemming the flow of ethnic
Germans from Poland. More than 140,000 ethnic Germans emigrated
from Poland to West Germany last year, and that number has already
been exceeded this year.
   Resolution of the economic and political issues cleared the way
for Kohl's trip, which initially was planned for the summer. It was
called off because of remaining differences between the two nations.
   Bonn had hoped to work out a reconciliation plan with Poland
before the 50th anniversary of the Sept. 1, 1939 invasion of Poland
by Nazi Germany, which set off World War II.
   Negotiations toward the West German-Polish summit were put on
hold during the spring talks between Poland's Solidarity trade
union and the Communist Party. Those negotiations Poland's freest
elections in more than four decades _which the opposition won by a
landslide _ and the Soviet bloc's first Cabinet not led by
Communists.
   Kohl will be the first Western leader to pay an official visit
to Poland since Tadeusz Mazowiecki was named premier in August.
   The talks had been frustrated by some prominent West German
politicians who said German territory lost to Poland after World
War II should be returned. National tensions still flare over the
40,000 square miles of German territory deeded to Poland after the
defeat of Nazi Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
