<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-SimVar     10-14 0118</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Sim Var,0119</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Cambodian Minister Dies in Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sim Var, founder of the Cambodian Democratic Party
and a former government leader, died in Paris, according to a
statement released Saturday. He was 85.
   Sim, who had lived in Paris since the Khmer Rouge took power in
Cambodia in 1974, served in several ministerial posts under Prince
Norodom Sihanouk following Cambodia's independence in 1954. In
1957, he led Cambodia's council of ministers.
   At the time the Khmer Rouge began their bloody four-year rule,
Sim was serving as ambassador to Tokyo.
   The statement released by the Movement for the Support of Khmer
Liberty did not give the cause of death or details of funeral
arrangements.
</TEXT>
