<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Ashes     10-14 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Ashes,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Tells Residents to Scatter Ashes in River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Municipal authorities in Hangzhou are asking
local residents to scatter the ashes of dead relatives in the river
so they don't pile up at crematoriums, an official report said
Saturday.
   To emphasize the point, the city Funeral and Internment
Administration will hold a ceremony next month to scatter 30 boxes
of ashes into the Qiantang River, the People's Daily said.
   Cremation is required in most places in China because of a
shortage of land for burial. But with 7,500 people dying each year
in Hangzhou, an eastern city of fewer than 2 million, even their
ashes are becoming bulky, the paper said.
   Most families leave them in urns at the city crematorium and
visit to pay respects at the annual Qing Ming festival.
   Several late Chinese leaders asked before death to have their
ashes scattered on mountains and rivers, and the paper quoted
Hangzhou Vice Mayor Wang Jizhong as saying that extending this to
everyone would be ``good for the country.''
   Authorities stressed the choice was up to the individual.
   The paper did not mention any possible harm to rivers. China has
a serious water pollution problem, with 80 percent of its rivers
polluted by raw sewage and untreated industrial waste.
</TEXT>
