<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Salaries     10-14 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Salaries,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Men Earn Twice As Much As Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average Japanese company employee earned
$27,000 last year, but the typical male earned more than twice as
much as his female counterpart, according to a government study
reported Saturday.
   The average annual income for Japan's 38 million company
employees, including bonuses, was up by $915, or 3.5 percent from
the previous year, the National Tax Agency said.
   The agency said the average female company employee earned
$15,800, less than half the average man's $33,100. The figures
include part-time employees who worked for the entire 12-month
period.
   Bonuses, given twice a year at most Japanese companies,
increased by 6.5 percent, the largest rise since 1979 when the
increase was 8.6 percent. The larger bonuses contributed greatly to
last year's income increase, the nationally circulated newspaper
Mainichi Shimbun quoted the agency as saying.
   The average net disposable income after adjustment for inflation
grew by 2.9 percent from a year earlier, helped mainly by the
larger bonuses and an income tax cut, the agency said.
   About 34 million, or 90 percent, of the company employees paid
income tax last year, the report said. It said the average worker
paid about $1,690.
   In comparison, the average self-employed person, other than
doctors and lawyers, paid only $1,440 in taxes, while farmers paid
an average of $1,010.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
