<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vatican-AIDS     10-14 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vatican-AIDS,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican to Hold International AIDS Conference Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican will hold an international
conference on AIDS next month, with participants including the
scientists who discovered the virus, officials said Saturday.
   The conference is scheduled for Nov. 13-15 and is being
organized by the Vatican's Council for Health Workers.
   Among those expected to attend are Robert Gallo of the United
States and Luc Montagner of France, credited with discovering the
AIDS virus.
   Pope John Paul II has called for compassion for AIDS victims but
opposes promotion of condoms to prevent the spread of the disease.
The Roman Catholic Church opposes artificial forms of birth control.
   The Vatican said last year it would hold a conference on AIDS,
or acquired immune deficiency syndrome. AIDS is caused by a virus
that attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible
to a wide variety of diseases.
   AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual contact but also
can be spread through transfusions of blood or the sharing of
contaminated hypodermic needles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
