<FIRST>r i AM-Mohammed'sBirthday     10-14 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mohammed's Birthday,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifteen Dead as Violence Breaks Out at Moslem Celebrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslems and Hindus fought each other and
police in the central city of Indore during a Moslem festival
Saturday marking the birth of the prophet Mohammed, and at least 14
people were killed, news reports said.
   In Karachi, Pakistan, snipers opened fire on a religious parade
held in Mohammed's honor after some marchers shouted slogans
against the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran, police said.
   One person was killed and another eight were wounded, including
a Pakistani army officer, local authorities said.
   Tens of thousands of people were celebrating the birth in 570 of
Islam's prophet, Mohammed.
   Press Trust of India said mobs burned several houses, six fire
trucks and a shantytown in Indore, 410 miles south of New Delhi.
   United News of India said 14 people were killed and 100 injured,
including 11 policemen. Press Trust of India put the death toll at
15 and said 75 people were injured, at least 22 of them seriously.
   UNI said a curfew was imposed and that police were told to shoot
violators. It said arson was reported mainly from five areas of
Indore, a city of 830,000 people.
   Neither news agency said how the violence started or how the
casualties occurred, but both said violence started ``following a
religious procession,'' an apparent reference to a morning rally to
celebrate Id ul-Milad un-Nabi, which marks the 1419th anniversary
of Mohammed's birth.
   Communal clashes frequently erupt in India during Hindu and
Moslem festivals.
   Moslems make up 11 percent of India's 880 million people. Hindus
comprise 82 percent of the population.
   People marching and riding in brightly colored vehicles, buses,
bicycles and horse-drawn carriages paraded through the streets of
many Pakistani cities in observance of Mohammed's birth.
   The marchers in Karachi, Pakistan, belonged to the Sunni sect of
Islam, which represents the majority of Pakistan's 107 million
people. In Iran, the majority of people belong to the Shiite branch
of Islam.
   Witnesses said processionists screamed anti-Khomeini slogans as
they wound their way through the old quarter of the city, which is
dominated by Shiite Moslems.
</TEXT>
