<DOCNO> AP891014-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1157EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-Politics     10-14 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Politics,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Movement Targets Nine for Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-choice activists today named Sen. Jesse
Helms of North Carolina, Gov. Bob Martinez of Florida and seven
other anti-abortion officials as special targets for defeat in next
year's elections.
   Emboldened by triumphs in Congress and the Florida legislature
last week, the National Abortion Rights Action League announced its
``NARAL Nine'' at its 20th anniversary conference. NARAL, which
counts 350,000 members, is the political arm of the pro-choice
movement.
   ``We intend to reward our political allies. But we also intend
to punish our enemies,'' said Kate Michelman, NARAL's executive
director. ``To elected officials, we say: If you remain out of step
on abortion rights, you will soon be out of a job.''
   Also addressing the conference, which drew hundreds of
pro-choice leaders from around the nation, was David Dinkins, the
Democratic candidate for mayor in New York City. ``I come to you
today ... to say that we in New York will always fight to protect a
woman's right to choose,'' he said.
   ``We're for it. Not half for it and half against it,'' he
declared.
   ``When I become mayjor New York City, people will respect the
law and obey the law or they will be arrested, prosectued and
punished,'' Dinkins said. ``That goes for street criminals, for
rapists, for corrupters, and for anyone who breaks the law to block
any woman exercising her right to choose.''
   Michelman said that ``the NARAL Nine _ and they're just the top
tier _ is where we're going to concentrate our response. This means
a heavy investment,'' in next year's elections.
   The target list includes Republican state legislators who have
been particularly vocal and effective in leading anti-abortion
efforts in key states, abortion opponents expected to seek higher
office, and two Democrats who have been identified as opposing
abortion rights.
   They are:
   _Stephen Freind, a Republican state representative in
Pennsylvania. NARAL said he is sponsiring a bill that would ban
abortion after the 24th week of pregnancy.
   _Helms, the three-term Republican senator from North Carolina
who has been an outspoken opponent of legalized abortions. So far,
only one Democrat, a little-known county prosecutor, has announced
as a candidate to oppose Helms.
   _Craig James, a Republican congressman from Florida who narrowly
defeated a veteran Democrat in 1988. NARAL had already targeted him
in advertising.
   _Martinez, the Florida governor whose state legislature rejected
all his proposals for restricting abortion in a special session he
convened last week. His likely opponents include Democratic Rep.
Bill Nelson, who NARAL said has a record of opposing abortion
rights.
   _Tom Miller, Iowa's Democratic attorney general and candidate
for governor in 1990. Miller is described as a staunch
anti-abortion advocate who faces several pro-choice opponents in
the Democratic primary.
   _William O'Neill, Democratic governor of Connecticut, who faces
several likely opponents.
   _Kurt Pringle, Republican state representative in California,
who won his first term narrowly in 1988. He is from Orange County.
NARAL said California's legislative elections would be a special
target because anti-abortion forces have a narrow majority in the
state assembly.
   _Denny Smith, Republican congressman from Oregon, who won
narrowly in 1988.
   _Tom Tauke, Republican congressman from Iowa, who is an
anti-abortion candidate for the Senate in 1990, opposing Democratic
Sen. Tom Harkin's bid for a second term.
   The group is also involved in the 1989 races for governor in New
Jersey and Virginia, and on Thursday began airing ads on Virginia
television stations attacking anti-abortion Republican candidate
Marshall Coleman. It was also running ads in more than a dozen
Sunday newspapers.
   Michelman said the group plans to work in 1990 party primary
campaigns in an effort to defeat anti-abortion candidates.
   In Iowa, the group plans to run an independent expenditure
campaign against Miller. In Florida, Michelman said the group would
reassess its involvement in the governor's race if Nelson becomes
the Democratic nominee and he does not embrace a pro-choice
position.
   Dinkins paid tribute ``to the women and men of the Florida state
legislature and the U.S. House of Representatives for their actions
... to protect reproductive choice for all of America's women.''
   While the Florida legislature rebuffed Martinez, the House voted
216-206 to broaden the circumstances under which poor women may
obtain a federally financed abortion _ now allowed only if the
woman's life is in danger. The new measure would permit
taxpayer-paid abortions in cases of rape and incest as well.
   Dinkins also took note of the Supreme Court's ruling earlier
this year in a Missouri case, in which the high court gave the
states broader authority to regulate abortions.
   ``With the Webster decision, we learned that the Supreme Court
can be packed ... and rights once recognized must constantly be
renewed and defended in the political arena,'' Dinkins said.
   ``The nation's highest court is sending the struggle for
reproductive rights back to the grassroots _ to the governors'
mansions, state legislatures, city halls, neighborhoods, precincts
and streets of every city, town and village in the nation,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
