<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-InokiAttack     10-14 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Inoki Attack,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inoki Attacked by Knife-Wielding Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former professional wrestler Antonio Inoki was
attacked by a knife-wielding man Saturday while giving a speech
inside an auditorium in northern Japan, police said.
   Inoki, a member of Parliament best known in the United States
for his exhibition bout with boxer Muhammad Ali 13 years ago, was
hospitalized with a head injury that will require three weeks of
treatment, police in Fukushima said.
   They said the alleged assailant, a 39-year-old man, was subdued
by security officials at the Fukuoka Prefectural Aizu Gymnasium and
turned over to police.
   The attacker, armed with an 8-inch-long knife, ran onto the
stage of the gym while Inoki, an independent member of the House of
Councilors, was addressing about 2,000 people, police said.
   Inoki, 46, a guest speaker at a rock concert, was talking about
international exchanges through sports, they said.
   Inoki wrestled several times in the gym before winning election
to Parliament in July.
   No further details of the attack were immediately available.
   Inoki fought Ali in Japan in a widely ridiculed but inconclusive
match that purported to match the American boxing great with
Japan's finest wrestler.
</TEXT>
