<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     10-14 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daily Warns Against Protests, Blasts West German Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily on
Saturday served notice that the government will not allow
demonstrations by independent groups to mark the anniversary of the
founding of Czechoslovakia on Oct. 28.
   The newspaper Rude Pravo said ``several'' Czechoslovak dissident
groups hoped to demonstrate that day to mark 71 years of
Czechoslovak independence.
   Last year on the anniversary, riot police using water cannons
and tear gas dispersed a crowd of about 5,000 demanding more
freedom at home.
   ``Several illegal groups want to misuse the oncoming state
anniversary for confrontation with our state power,'' Rude Pravo
said.
   ``Nobody, at home or abroad, can expect us to vacate our
positions for anti-socialist forces (and) let the party lose its
influence on the course of events,'' it added.
   In a separate article, the newspaper blasted West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl for a speech Oct. 10 at the opening of the
Book Fair in Frankfurt in which he said the ``winds of freedom will
blow'' one day in Czechoslovakia.
   ``Poland has, in a very encouraging way, stepped forward on a
path of bigger freedom and more human rights and Hungary is about
to follow,'' Kohl said, referring to recent democratic reforms in
those Soviet bloc nations.
   ``That's why it is more than a mere dream that one day even in
Czechoslovakia and elsewhere the wind of freedom will blow,'' Kohl
said. He also urged Czechoslovak authorities to grant dissident
Vaclav Havel an exit visa so he could come to the fair to receive
its top prize.
   Havel has not received permission to travel to Frankfurt.
   ``It's hard to believe that at a time when East-West relations
are improving, Bonn comes with a strange concept of building a
common European Home,'' Rude Pravo said, accusing Kohl of acting
``as a teacher of nations'' and interfering in Czechoslovakia's
internal affairs.
   Although it enjoys one of the highest standards of living among
the seven Warsaw Pact nations, Czechoslovakia has taken one of the
hardest lines against dissent and has been reluctant to emulate
political and economic reforms under way in the Soviet bloc.
</TEXT>
