<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-NewPolitics Bjt   10-14 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-New Politics, Bjt,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Dynamics of Abortion Changing in Congress and Across the
Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Rep. John Rowland did an about-face
on the abortion issue a week before his planned announcement as a
candidate for Connecticut governor _ and offered ``I don't know''
when asked why he changed positions.
   Democrat Rep. W.G. Hefner also shifted and voted to soften the
ban on Medicaid-financed abortions. He reasoned that he previously
had been a target of abortion foes in his North Carolina district,
but that the political climate was starting to change.
   Other congressmen gave other reasons: Their wives had pressured
them, or they really meant to vote this way last time.
   But by any analysis, the changes in position by 27 members of
Congress on the issue of tax-financed abortions reflect a change in
the political dynamics of abortion.
   Republican Rep. Henry Hyde, whose name has been linked with the
Medicaid abortion restrictions known as the ``Hyde amendment'' for
a decade, put his finger on what had happened.
   ``They're perceiving their constituencies as pro-choice,'' he
said.
   Last week's events in Congress, in Florida's legislature, and in
the states holding elections this year, showed that the new
politics of abortion could have broadening implications.
   Republican strategists are clearly concerned about polls
suggesting voters are increasingly inclined to support continuing
legal abortions and to oppose candidates who want to limit those
rights. The Republican Party since Ronald Reagan's nomination in
1980 has had a strongly anti-abortion platform.
   ``This causes Republicans in general nervousness,'' said one
national Republican strategist. ``Abortion as an issue ...
definitely has changed for candidates at the governor and state
legislature level.'' Citing the sensitivity of the issue, the
strategist spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   While the depth of change remains subject to debate, all sides
called it a reaction to the Supreme Court's ruling last summer in
the Webster case. By giving states broader authority to regulate
abortions, the court made abortion _ and the prospect that abortion
rights could be taken away _ a more relevant issue in the states
and mobilized pro-choice groups.
   ``Clearly the pro-choice movement has outmaneuvered the pro-life
movement since `Webster,''' said Eddie Mahe, a Republican political
consultant.
   Emboldened by their successes, some Democrats have even begun to
think abortion may be that sought-after ``wedge'' issue _ an
emotion-packed weapon that could divide Republicans and draw back
to the Democratic Party young voters, aged 18 to 30, who began
drifting to Reagan and the Republicans a decade ago.
   The wedge, they hope, could be used to separate ideologically
conservative Republicans from those younger voters who were drawn
to the GOP on economic issues _ but who have never held the
conservative views on social issues that the ideological
conservatives and evangelical Republicans have.
   ``In 1980, a trend began that was a very serious threat to
Democrats _ losing younger voters,'' said Frank Greer, a Democratic
political consultant who has produced a groundbreaking appeal to
conservatives based on the abortion issue in Virginia.
   ``All of a sudden, young voters have awoken to the fact
Republicans are out of touch with their social concerns,'' Greer
said. ``I think it's a watershed political event, and you're seeing
it in Virginia.''
   Republicans dispute that view, and say the abortion issue is
still developing.
   ``One assumes the pro-life people will get their act together,''
said Mahe, a consultant to the Republican National Committee in
last year's presidential race. ``They will attempt to frame the
issue in ways that benefit them. Then we'll see. This is still
unknown.''
   But the change has been felt in Congress and the states already.
   One result is that abortion opponents no longer instill the same
fear they once did among members of Congress who had seen
pro-choice candidates such as former Sen. Dick Clark of Iowa lose
in 1978 in defeats laid to the abortion issue.
   ``In the past, the only people we heard from were people who say
in no circumstances should abortion be performed,'' said Hefner,
who contended his switch on the issue merely returned his position
to the way he had voted in years past. ``Other people, who
represent what I think is a more reasonable position, are being
heard from more.''
   The House's narrow 216-206 vote was to broaden the circumstances
under which poor women may obtain a federally financed abortion to
include rape and incest, as well as the existing provision for
cases where the mother's life is in danger.
   In Florida's legislature, the anti-abortion Republican Gov. Bob
Martinez suffered total defeat in the special session he convened
to impose new restrictions on abortion.
   And in states such as New Jersey and Virginia, abortion emerged
as a powerful issue in the hands of Democratic candidates for
governor who support continuing legal abortions.
   In Virginia, the example is striking. Democrat Douglas Wilder
has moved into a lead, according to independent polls, after three
weeks of airing television advertising that attacks his Republican
opponent as trying to take away a woman's right to an abortion.
   In a conservative state that was once capital of the
Confederacy, Wilder's ads are crafted to appeal to conservatives,
arguing that his opponent would take away rights and allow
government intrusion in personal affairs.
   Wilder, incidentally, is seeking to become the first black
elected governor of a state.
   ``If anyone had bet me that a black man would be running for
governor of Virginia, and winning, using abortion as an issue, I
probably would have lost every nickel I had,'' mused liberal
pollster Harrison Hickman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
