<FIRST>r w AM-US-Japan     10-14 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leadership Can Overcome US-Japanese Friction, Solarz Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese and U.S. leaders must work to curb
the growing criticism coming from opposite sides of the Pacific,
says a senior member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   ``I am concerned about the tone of the relationship and the
extent to which more and more it has become subject of criticism in
Congress and outside, with comparable echoes in Japan,'' Rep.
Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y. told a gathering Friday of the Washington
Foreign Correspondents Association.
   ``We need leadership to make clear that while the relationship
is not without differences and difficulties, it is of enormous
benefit,'' said Solarz.
   He is one of the most influential Democrats engaged in foreign
affairs. Fellow party members are among Washington's staunchest
critics of Japanese trade policies.
   Solarz commented on a recent U.S. opinion poll showing that the
loss of American jobs to imports, the multibillion dollar trade
deficit with Japan and heavy Japanese investment in U.S. real
estate and industry have prompted many Americans to regard Japan as
posing a greater threat to their future than that posed by the
Soviet Union under President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Americans ``are the victims of our own success,'' Solarz said.
``We helped build the Japanese economy from the ashes of war. We
benefit greatly from their economic progress, we ought to find ways
to continue to benefit. Japan is certainly not a threat to the
United States.''
   He also acknowledged that the threat of war with the Soviet
Union is declining, thanks to Gorbachev's policies of restructuring
and openness. Solarz, who chairs the House Asia-Pacific
subcommittee, closely follows Europe because he represents a
Brooklyn, N.Y., district with people of mainly European ancestry,
including many recent immigrants.
   Asked if the United States should advocate independence for the
Baltic Soviet Republics in the western part of the U.S.S.R., even
if meant Gorbachev's ouster, Solarz said it was a mistake to link
U.S. policy ``with the survival of a particular political leader.''
   ``If Gorbachev were forced to resign it would be a source of
dismay, given the possibilities of his policies, but ... hopefully
a new leadership would be committed to the same policy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
