<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     10-14 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Bolster Security at U.S. Facilities as Dissidents Press Demands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police bolstered security at U.S.
government facilities Saturday as the nation's main dissident
alliance demanded the recall of the U.S. ambassador and defended an
attack on his residence.
   Leaders of Chonminyon, an alliance of dissident groups, said at
a news conference that the attack ``reflected the will of the
people.'' The group earlier issued a statement demanding an end to
ties with the United States.
   Six radical students stormed U.S. Ambassador Donald Gregg's
house early Friday and went on a half-hour rampage, hurling tear
gas and breaking objects with iron bars before police seized them.
   Gregg and his wife escaped unharmed.
   Police said security had been tightened at all U.S. government
facilities since the attack.
   Embassy officials said they would review the security system of
Gregg's residence in downtown Seoul. Unlike the U.S. Embassy, it is
not guarded by U.S. Marines but by South Korean police.
   In addition to the attack on the Greggs' home, police reported
anti-U.S. protests on 26 campuses in seven cities Friday.
   On Saturday, about 400 radical students chanting ``Yankee go
home!'' hurled firebombs and rocks when police blocked an anti-U.S.
march out of Sogang University.
   In its statement, Chonminyon demanded the United States recall
Gregg, contending he supported military rule when he served as CIA
station chief in Seoul in the 1970s.
   ``We ask you to immediately recall Gregg to return South
Korean-U.S. relations to normal,'' the statement said.
   The dissident alliance also called for the withdrawal of the
43,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea and an end to U.S. demands
for greater access to South Korean markets.
   ``The presence of U.S. forces on the Korean peninsula serves as
an obstacle to peace in the region,'' the group said.
   Dissidents and radical students have called for Gregg's recall
and an end to U.S. trade pressure. The United States wants Seoul to
end import barriers to help correct its trade surplus with
Washington.
   The radicals also have demanded President Roh Tae-woo cancel his
trip Sunday to Washington for talks with President Bush, charging
Roh is seeking to improve U.S. ties to bolster his conservative
government.
   The radicals are a small but vocal minority.
   Most South Koreans support Seoul's alliance with Washington and
the presence of U.S. troops here.
</TEXT>
