<DOCNO> AP891014-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion-NIH     10-14 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-NIH,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Litmus Test for New NIH Director?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion-New Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives were glad to read that abortion
reportedly is one of the issues being used by the White House to
screen candidates for the job of director of the National
Institutes of Health.
   But a member of the search committee that recommended potential
candidates said she hoped the volatile issue would not ``preclude
our getting the very best scientific leadership'' for NIH.
   One of the candidates for the job, Washington University
Chancellor William Danforth, brother of Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo.,
was asked for his views recently in a call from the white House
personnel office, according to an Oct. 6 report in Science, the
journal of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
   Science quoted an unidentified colleague as saying Danforth was
asked what his views were on abortion and on fetal-tissue research.
The magazine quoted the source as saying Danforth told the caller:
``If that is all you want to know, I'm not your man.''
   The magazine said Danforth declined to comment on the
conversation, but said the NIH job was ``not my thing'' and that he
was ``wedded'' to the St. Louis university.
   The search committee that recommended names of potential
candidates did not assess abortion views during the process, said
Virginia Weldon, a member of the panel and vice president for
scientific affairs at Monsanto Co. in St. Louis. ``We didn't
discuss that,'' she said.
   She said she was not surprised the White House would ask about
abortion views ``since it's a major issue in our country today.''
However, she added, ``I think it would be very unfortunate if that
issue precluded our getting the very best scientific leadership for
the National Institutes of Health.''
   Asked Friday about the Since report, Gary Bauer, president of
the conservative Family Research Council and a former domestic
policy aide in the Reagan White House, said he ``would expect the
White House to be asking those questions.''
   Conservatives have said fetal-tissue research is an issue they
will be watching closely and one that could erupt into a firestorm.
NIH currently has a moratorium on using fetuses from elective
abortions in federally funded research. An NIH advisory committee
last year concluded that using fetal tissue for research is
acceptable, but Health and Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan
has not acted on the panel's report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
