<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Waite     10-14 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waite,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 1,000 Days, Still No Word on Terry Waite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Waite, the Anglican Church envoy
who sought to free American hostages in Lebanon and wound up being
kidnapped, marks his 1,000th day in captivity Sunday with no word
on his fate.
   Nothing has been heard of the envoy since he left the Riviera
Hotel in Moslem west Beirut at 7.30 p.m. on Jan. 20, 1987, to meet
with the Shiite Moslem kidnappers of two Americans he was trying to
free.
   In England, prayer vigils organized by the Church Army, the
Church of England's evangelical branch, were held Friday to mark
Waite's 1,000th day as a hostage.
   ``I really do think that he is still alive,'' his mother, Lena,
said. ``I feel he is. He would hate to be shut up like that, but I
am sure he will come through all right.''
   Waite was on his fifth mission to Beirut when he disappeared. He
told his tough Druse bodyguards he did not want them to escort him
to the clandestine meeting at an undisclosed site.
   Well informed sources said at the time that Waite was driven to
the home of a Shiite Moslem physician who had acted as a
go-between. He was apparently to contact representatives of Islamic
Jihad, which holds U.S. hostages Terry Anderson and Thomas
Sutherland.
   Waite never returned, and it is widely believed he became a
captive of the Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem extremists.
   The 50-year-old envoy, a policeman's son who became the personal
emissary of Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, is one of five
Britons missing in Lebanon.
   Thirteen other Westerners, including eight Americans, are
missing. All Americans are believed held by Shiite factions.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, has been held longer than any hostage. He was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
   Several rumors about Waite's fate have circulated. He has been
reported ill, killed, wounded while trying to escape, smuggled to
Iran in a coffin to stand trial as an American spy, and ransomed
for $7 million.
   No group has claimed to hold him and there have been no
photographs or videotapes to prove he is alive. The British
government says no demands have been made for his freedom.
   But other Western hostages freed since Waite disappeared have
reported seeing a man believed to be the towering 6-foot, 7-inch
Briton in an underground prison.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt, who says he will pursue every lead
to try to free Waite, has accused the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God, of holding Waite.
   Hezbollah, believed to be the umbrella for groups holding most
of the Westerners, denies the allegation.
   Ten days after Waite vanished, Runcie said the envoy had left
written instructions that he wanted no ransom paid or rescue
mission attempted if he was kidnapped during his mission.
   Waite's disappearance came months after the disclosure that the
United States had traded arms for hostages.
   Three Americans held by Islamic Jihad were freed following the
delivery of U.S. weapons to Iran in 1985-86 during its war with
Iraq.
   Waite had been credited with securing the release of the three _
the Rev. Benjamin Weir, the Rev. Laurence Jenco, and David Jacobson
_ until the U.S. dealings with Tehran were disclosed in November
1986.
   There have been reports Islamic Jihad decided to hold Waite
responsible for failing to secure the freedom of 15 pro-Iranian
extremists imprisoned in Kuwait for a string of 1983 bombings.
Freeing those men had been Islamic Jihad's main demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
