<FIRST>r i AM-Jordan-Election 1stLd-Writethru   10-14 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0542,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kingdom Launches First National Campaign in 22 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to ADD number of voters, details on Palestinians'
campaign. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loyalists and royalists rubbed shoulders
with communists and Islamic fundamentalists Saturday to register as
candidates in this kingdom's first general election in 22 years.
   ``It means we are returning back to democratic life,'' said poet
and journalist Abdul-Rahim Omar, who is seeking a parliamentary
seat in the capital. ``It means we will again have an independent
legislative authority.''
   Omar held one of the small blue number tags officials passed out
to control the flow of candidates as registration began in Amman.
   Officials have said 1,000 or more people are considering a run
for the 80 parliamentary seats being contested Nov. 8.
   It will be Jordan's first nationwide balloting since April 1967
_ a few months before the Middle East war with Israel. Of the
country's 3 million people, 1 million are registered voters.
   Candidates have three days to register, and officials then have
three days to reject those not considered qualified. Anyone
rejected by the regional governor can appeal to the courts, which
must rule in another three days.
   Although Jordanian law prohibits members of banned organizations
from seeking election, officials have hinted they will permit
members of the outlawed Communist Party and other leftist groups to
run.
   The law allowed official campaigning to begin Saturday, and
Amman residents awoke to find campaign banners suspended over city
streets and leaflets stuffed under windshield wipers of their cars.
   ``There is no glory except in Islam'' proclaimed a banner
hoisted by two Islamic candidates above a busy street in the Jebel
Hussein district.
   ``Woman is half of the society. She is the one who raises the
future generations,'' announced another banner directed at women,
who are taking part in nationwide voting for the first time in
Jordan's history.
   Women gained the vote in 1974, but only a handful of local
district elections have been held since then.
   Nationwide voting was impossible after 1967, when Israel
captured the West Bank, because that territory contained half the
60 seats in Jordan's old Parliament.
   But King Hussein last year renounced claims to the West Bank in
favor of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and the government
drew up plans for a new Parliament that will omit representation
for the West Bank for the first time since 1950.
   The Parliament elected in 1967 was suspended in 1974 and revived
a decade later with a few elections to fill gaps caused by death.
It was generally compliant to government will, despite a few vocal
critics.
   Most candidates and analysts have said the new Parliament will
take a more active role, especially following the widespread
rioting that erupted in April to protest price increases.
   Scores of candidates gathered Saturday morning at the Amman
governor's office to register. Tribal sheiks in flowing robes
waited in line, chatting with businessmen in suits and Islamic
fundamentalists.
   ``It feels great to have democracy back to our country under the
leadership of his majesty, King Hussein,'' said Hamad Abu Jamus, a
retired army brigadier general seeking election in Amman.
   ``We have been waiting for this for the past 22 years,'' he said.
   Dr. Ali Hawamdeh, a leader of the Moslem Brotherhood, said he
expected his and other Islamic groups to back about 30 candidates,
seeking morality, clean government, social justice and a hard line
toward Israel.
   The PLO has distanced itself from the election to avoid a
conflict with Jordan, but many candidates are appealing to
Palestinian sentiments, especially in Amman, where some 70 percent
of people come from Palestinian families.
   ``We salute the children of the stones,'' proclaimed a banner
raised by candidate Carlos Dames, referring to youths of the
Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
