<FIRST>r a AM-CrabPotMolesters Bjt   10-14 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crab Pot Molesters, Bjt,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crab Thieves Parade on Bridge for Punishment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four young men who pulled crab traps from
the St. Johns River while ``looking for a good time'' on a holiday
weekend began paying their their debt to society Saturday _ by
parading on a bridge with signs admitting their acts.
   The men carried hand-lettered signs reading: ``It is a felony
punishable by prison and-or a $5,000 fine to molest crab pots. I
know because I molested one.''
   As they trudged the two-tenths of a mile to the top of a bridge
over the St. Johns River and back down, the four were accompanied
by Michael West, a probation officer from this town about 50 miles
south of Jacksonville.
   All four refused to talk to reporters. A few motorists honked at
them, but no problems occurred.
   Jacksonville insurance salesman Stephen Michael Kittredge, one
of the four men caught raiding seven traps in May, said earlier
that too much beer and too little common sense were to blame.
   ``It was Memorial Day weekend. We were just a bunch of guys
looking for a good time. We were probably a little bit drunk. We
were wrong. We readily admit we were wrong,'' the 23-year-old
Kittredge said.
   He and pals John Shiver Snelling, 24, Gregory Coleman Dyer, 24,
and David Todd Harris, 23, agreed to walk with the
poster-board-size placards for four weekends in exchange for having
prosecutors drop charges.
   ``This a felony situation, and you are looking at guys that all
have careers,'' said Putnam County probation director Vicky Weaver.
   Robert Scholl, the fisherman who lost 30 crabs to the men, said
the public humiliation is not enough punishment. He wanted them
convicted and fined the maximum.
   ``You could shoot them at daylight and that might not satisfy
him,'' countered Ms. Weaver.
   Assistant State Attorney Richard Whitson said the public display
will do more to help the crabbing industry than jailing the four
men.
   Each man must also pay Scholl five times the cost of the lost
catch, or an estimated $675 each, Ms. Weaver said.
   Though unhappy with the punishment, Scholl acknowledged that
``it's going to be very expensive crab meat.''
   Fishermen leave the underwater traps unattended for hours,
attached to floating markers, while they make their rounds, picking
up their catch and replacing bait.
   A crab fisherman for 17 years, Scholl estimates he loses $1,000
a year in equipment to thefts, not counting the lost catch.
   The men walking the bridge Saturday also will carry signs on the
municipal dock and at the county courthouse on subsequent weekends.
   Kittredge and Harris, a real estate broker, live in
Jacksonville. Snelling is a law student living in Atlanta, and Dyer
is a sales representative in Fort Myers for a medical supply
company.
   Kittredge said the four men were spending the weekend on a
houseboat when a trap got caught in a boat propeller and rose to
the surface. They were arrested June 6 by sheriff's officers who
had been tipped off to the men's boat number.
   ``It looked like lunch in the pot to them. It could have been a
$5,000 lunch,'' Whitson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     10-14 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet To Dissolve Secret Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet said he plans
to dissolve the secret police agency that human rights activists
blamed Saturday for some of the most brutal and sinister crimes of
his iron-fisted regime.
   Pinochet, answering questions from local reporters Friday in the
southern town of Coihaique, said the National Information Center
will be scrapped before an elected civilian government takes power
in March.
   He said the agency will be phased out `because it is an organ
that served this government.''
   He did not elaborate, saying only: ``I can't say now what will
happen to its men.''
   Roberto Garreton, legal chief for the Solidarity Vicariate human
rights group, said the agency inflicted horrendous crimes on the
populace.
   ``Just as Pinochet recognizes, the CNI was at the service of his
government, which is to say at his service and not at the service
of the country. That's why the institution will disappear when the
government changes,'' he said.
   Pinochet, the army commander who seized power in a bloody 1973
coup, lost a referendum a year ago on extending his rule to 1997.
The loss obliged him to call elections, scheduled for December 14,
to pick a civilian successor who will take power March 11.
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press, Garreton
said the secret police force ``has been linked to the most sinister
(activities) of the regime in recent years'' including the torture
and killing of leftists.
   The Solidarity Vicariate, sponsored by the local Roman Catholic
Church, is among the country's most respected human rights agencies.
   All three presidential candidates pledged to abolish the police
agency if elected.
   The agency was created in 1977 to replace another secret police
force, the National Intelligence Directorate, after it was linked
to the assassination of prominent dissidents abroad. The CNI's
directors all have been army generals, and most of its officers are
armed forces members.
   Former Finance Minister Hernan Buchi, opposition leader Patricio
Aylwin and independent businessman Francisco Errazuriz are running
for the presidency. Aylwin, backed by a 17-party center-left
coalition that triumphed in the referendum, leads by a substantial
margin in most polls.
   In his comments to reporters in Coihaique, 1,350 miles south of
Santiago, Pinochet also hinted at military action if armed forces
members are persecuted by the new government.
   ``The day they touch one of my men, the state of law ends,'' he
declared. ``I say this only once, and won't say it again, but they
know that's how it is.''
   Texts of his exchange with reporters were carried Saturday by
Santiago newspapers.
   Pinochet previously has warned he will not accept prosecution,
under the new government, of armed forces members on charges of
human rights abuse. Hundreds of cases of illegal arrest, torture
and other rights violations are pending in the Chilean courts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
