<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1446EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Summerville     10-14 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Summerville,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Recovering But Scars Remain More Than Three Weeks After Hugo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUMMERVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three weeks after Hurricane
Hugo slammed into this bedroom community, the buzz of chainsaws
drowns out most sounds as the town struggles toward recovery.
   Schools are open again, the power is on, traffic is heavy on
Main Street and most businesses have reopened, but physical and
emotional scars from the hurricane run deep and will not be eased
anytime soon, residents say.
   ``Things will probably never be the same,'' resident Jessica
Brown said recently. ``This neighborhood is still in shock about a
lot of things.''
   Her house in the College Park subdivision suffered extensive
water damage when the Sept. 21 hurricane lifted the roof, moved the
house off its foundation and sent rain cascading into the attic.
   ``Things have hit us pretty hard,'' Mrs. Brown said. ``I lost a
10-month-old baby a week before the storm and we were trying to get
our lives back together. Then this happened.''
   An insurance adjuster has yet to make it to her house, but she
said she doesn't really mind ``because a lot of people are a lot
worse off than me.''
   Across South Carolina, the hurricane left 18 dead, 270,000
jobless, at least 50,000 homeless and $4 billion or more in damage.
   President Bush made a quick, unscheduled visit to this community
of 18,000 as part of his trip to the state a week after Hugo roared
through. He promised federal aid, and a few days later, the Federal
Emergency Management Agency opened a disaster center here.
   While other cities and towns such as Charleston, 20 miles to the
south; McClellanville and Sumter were hit harder and still struggle
to get life's necessities back, Summerville is edging toward
recovery.
   But the reminders of Hugo remain.
   Summerville was settled in the 1700s as South Carolina's first
resort by wealthy Charlestonians who sought refuge from the
disease-bearing mosquitoes which swarmed coastal marshes in the
summer.
   The town's centerpiece, Azalea Park, was awash during the spring
with crimson, lavender and white blossoms. Today, it is littered
with fallen pine trees and massive oaks now twisted and splintered
like matchsticks.
   Cars still have plastic covering smashed windows, piles of tree
limbs line the curbs waiting for removal, plywood has replaced
broken store windows and carpenters are busy patching damaged roofs.
   Yet, residents say, good things were spawned by the destruction.
   Neighbors finally got to know each other as they shared food,
cooked on outdoor grills and helped clear streets of fallen limbs.
   ``I'm closer to my friends and neighbors, some we didn't really
know,'' Leanne Junkins said. ``The friendship and caring that all
these people had for everybody else without putting a price tag on
it _ you can't beat that kind of love.''
   Now that schools have reopened, people are back to work and into
a routine again, it has been easier to cope with the devastation,
Mrs. Junkins said.
   In Diane Turocy's neighborhood, she became something of a
celebrity when a picture of her and President Bush was flashed
around the globe. It was a moment she never expected.
   ``We're starting to settle into a routine. We're just trying to
get on with our lives,'' she said, when a Secret Service agent
knocked at her door on the morning of Sept. 29.
   ``I greeted him in my nightgown and he said, `Would you like to
meet the president? You have two minutes.'''
   The visit ``was just a tremendous boost for a small town,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
