<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Media     10-14 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Media,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Journalist Named Editor of Government Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran Solidarity journalist and
political activist was named editor in chief of the government
daily, the state news agency reported Saturday. The move further
consolidates Solidarity's growing media presence.
   Dariusz Fikus, 57, was chosen by Solidarity Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki to replace Janusz Durmala, a Communist Party
member, as head of the Rzeczpospolita daily, the PAP news agency
said.
   Fikus said in a telephone interview he hoped the newspaper would
represent the different groups in the government and appeal to the
average citizen.
   ``A coalition is in power now, so one should present different
interests, show various stands, but at the same time depict the
stand of the government with affection,'' Fikus said.
   The new non-Communist government was confirmed by Parliament
Sept. 12. It consists of Solidarity supporters and members of its
two coalition parties as well as the Communist Party.
   Fikus is the second Solidarity member to take over a major state
media organization since the East bloc's first non-Communist
government was formed.
   Last month, Mazowiecki named opposition journalist Andrzej
Drawicz to head the committee that controls state television and
radio.
   Fikus has been a journalist for more than 30 years, first in the
Communist-controlled press and later in independent and
Solidarity-linked publications.
   A Communist Party member from 1959-81, Fikus developed links to
the independent oppostion in the late 1970s and took part in talks
on Solidarity's access to radio and television during the union's
first legal phase in 1980-81.
   He said that journalists who decided they did not want to work
under him as editor would be free to leave. Until now, the paper
has been run mainly by members of the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
