<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos     10-14 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planned Interment of Marcos Is Temporary, Family Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
was to be interred Sunday in a shedlike mausoleum that family
members insist is a temporary entombment until his body can be
buried in his homeland.
   The mausoleum was contructed last week largely by volunteers on
a hillside overlooking the Valley of the Temples Memorial Park,
said Joe Lazo, head of a Honolulu-based group called the Friends of
Marcos.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino has repeatedly refused to
allow Marcos' body to be returned to the Philippines, saying it
could create unrest by Marcos supporters.
   In an effort to prevent the Philippine Supreme Court from
overturning Mrs. Aquino's ban, government attorneys last week
accused the Marcos family of plotting to assassinate Mrs. Aquino,
but gave few details.
   A funeral Mass for Marcos was held Friday night, attended by
more than 1,500 people who packed into St. Theresa cathedral,
Honolulu's largest Roman Catholic church.
   Monsignor Domingo Nebres of the Philippines delivered the eulogy
and likened Marcos to Jesus for suffering and forgiving those who
betrayed him.
   ``Christ was a victim of the people's power, so Marcos was a
victim of the people's power,'' said Nebres, who had been Marcos'
friend for 12 years.
   ``My beloved president would say, `Do not cry for me. ... Cry
for your country,''' he said.
   Marcos died in exile Sept. 28 at age 72 following nine months in
a hospital for a variety of major ailments.
   During the Mass, his widow, Imelda, covered her face with a
black veil and clutched a silver rosary.
   When the casket was opened following the hour-long Mass, Mrs.
Marcos kissed the clear plastic covering it and placed a single
white lily there.
   She made no comment to reporters.
</TEXT>
