<HEAD>Eds: SUBS LAWRENCE, Kan.-dated 3rd item to CORRECT quote in penultimate
graf to grandfather sted father.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Landon said he prevailed over NBC
when network officials asked him to change the title of his
film-in-progress, ``Where Pigeons Go To Die.''
   Landon was in Lawrence to film the story, based on a book by
Robert Campbell of the same title, about a boy and his grandfather
who raise homing pigeons.
   ``They asked me and I said no,'' Landon said Friday, adding that
the network officials thought the title was too long and didn't
like having the word ``die'' in it.
   ``You owe some kind of respect to the man who wrote the book,''
Landon said. ``I think they liked something stunning like, `Welcome
Home Grandfather.'''
   Landon is producing the movie for NBC, and the film could air on
the network as early as February. He also wrote the screenplay and
stars in it with Art Carney.
   ``Where Pigeons Go To Die'' is ``a flashback, the remembrances
of a man who 40 years before had a special relationship with his
grandfather,'' Landon said.
   Landon said about 40 percent of the shooting will take place in
Lawrence, a college town about 35 miles west of Kansas City, Mo.
