<FIRST>r w AM-ColombiansExtradited     10-14 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombians Extradited,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Reputed Drug Traffickers Brought to United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. authorities flew three suspected drug
traffickers to jails in Florida and Michigan early Saturday in the
second extradition from Colombia since emergency measures were
imposed there in August.
   One of them has already been convicted, in absentia, in Detroit.
Florida prosecutors called one of the others a ``big fish.''
   U.S. marshals said the three were turned over to U.S. officials
in Colombia about 3 a.m. and flown to Miami, where one was dropped
off. The flight then continued to Orlando and Detroit to deliver
the other two. Marshals said the three were being held in
``secure'' detention facilities in the three areas, but declined to
be more specific.
   The extraditions bring to four the number of people brought to
this country from Colombia since President Virgilio Barco imposed
emergency measures against drug traffickers Aug. 18.
   ``I commend President Barco and the government of Colombia for
their continued diligence in the war against narcoterrorists,''
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said in a statement.
   ``The Colombian people are setting an example for the world as
they continue to extradite international drug traffickers in the
face of continued threats and acts of intimidation,'' Thornburgh
said.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel identified the three
defendants as Ana Rodriguez de Tamayo, Roberto Peter Carlini-Arrico
and Bernardo Pelaez Roldan.
   The U.S. Marshals Service said de Tamayo, 50, faces charges in
Miami of cocaine importation and conspiracy to possess with intent
to distribute cocaine.
   Carlini-Arrico, 38, faces federal charges of possession with
intent to distribute 7,000 pounds of marijuana and importing 7,000
pounds of marijuana in the Middle District of Florida at Orlando,
marshals said.
   Three other defendants in that federal case are in custody, and
the trial is scheduled for November, Runkel said.
   Assistant State Attorney Andy Zelman said Carlini-Arrico is
accused by state authorities of smuggling more than a ton of
cocaine during the mid-1980s.
   State prosecutor Peter Antonacci said the 1986 state charges
against Carlini-Arrico consist of one count each of racketeering,
conspiracy to commit racketeering, cocaine trafficking and
conspiracy to traffic the drug. Each state count carries a 15-year
mandatory minimum sentence.
   Carlini-Arrico, who had Florida addresses in Boca Raton and
Gainesville, fled the country following the state indictments, said
Antonacci.
   ``He is a big fish,'' said Antonacci. ``We are glad we'll get a
chance to prosecute.''
   Pelaez, 44, was convicted in absentia in Detroit in March 1984
of conspiracy to possess with intent to distribute cocaine.
   Barco allowed extradition among other emergency measures that
followed the assassination of a leading presidential candidate who
was an outspoken foe of the drug trade.
   Colombia's supreme court has upheld the decision to resume
extraditions to the United States. In 1987, it had blocked
extraditions.
   The first reputed drug trafficker extradited since the emergency
actions went into effect was Eduardo Martinez Romero, who was taken
to the United States on Sept. 6 to face money laundering charges
brought in March in Atlanta.
   Since Barco imposed the emergency measures, drug traffickers in
Colombia have declared ``total war'' on the government. They have
been held responsible for setting off more than 150 bombs that have
killed more than 10 people and wounded at least 200.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891014-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1624EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BusinessCouncil     10-14 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Council,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Business Leaders See Some Long-Range Benefit in Market Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's top business leaders
tallied losses in their personal stock portfolios on Saturday, but
many said the market collapse a day earlier could be a boon if its
cools a corporate takeover fever.
   The 190-point plunge of the Dow Jones industrial average Friday
was a surprise intruder at the Business Council's fall meeting,
held at a posh resort in the Blue Ridge mountains.
   The market's plunge wiped out $200 billion of stock values
overall, leaving many of the executives poorer, on paper, than when
they arrived.
   George Keller, retired chairman of Chevron Corp., said he
figured the one-day market drop had cost him $250,000. Other
executives traded similar tales of woe.
   Despite the precipitous drop in stock values for their
companies, however, many of the executives expressed belief that
some good could come from the market correction if it ends the
takeover fever that has been driving stock prices this year.
   Much of the loss occurred in the last hour of trading on Friday
after news reports that the pending takeover of UAL Corp., parent
of United Airlines, was in jeopardy because of financing problems.
   This sparked fears among stock traders that the surge of
multibillion-dollar corporate takeovers was coming to an end and
helped trigger the selling frenzy, many analysts believe.
   Since many of the corporate executives have had to fend off
unwanted takeovers in the past, something that dampened this
activity could be seen as a welcome development in their eyes.
   For example, one executive at the meeting, American Airlines
President Robert L. Crandall, is currently facing a takeover bid
from New York real estate developer Donald Trump.
   Asked if Friday's developments could help him fend off Trump's
bid, Crandall merely smiled and said, ``No comment.''
   Rand V. Araskog, chairman of ITT Corp., was more blunt in his
criticism of the Reagan and Bush administrations for doing nothing
to curb speculative takeovers.
   ``We have a very nervous marketplace,'' he said. ``Are the
lawyers and investment bankers in charge or is the president of the
United States in charge?''
   He said the whole attitude of deregulation of the marketplace
over the past eight years was not contributing to the long-term
growth prospects of the United States.
   Allen Murray, chairman of Mobil Corp., said Friday's market
decline could end up being a good thing if market speculators are
replaced by long-term investors.
   ``I am anxious to see the market move up, but I am anxious to
see it move up on investments and not speculation,'' he said.
``That will be better for the country.''
   Many of the business executives were hesitant to make
predictions about what might happen when the markets open again
Monday.
   ``The markets have had enormous growth and now an adjustment
process has set in,'' said IBM Chairman John Akers. ``The markets
do what the markets want to do.''
   While Murray denied that any crisis atmosphere existed, John F.
McGillicuddy, chairman of Manufacturers Hanover Corp., said,
``Anytime you have the market drop by (190) points, if you aren't
concerned, there's something wrong with you.''
   General Motors Chairman Roger Smith refused to make a prediction
on whether Friday's plunge would be followed by further selling
Monday, saying it was hard to guess what the market's ``herd
instinct'' might do.
   ITT's Araskog agreed. ``Everybody can tell everybody to be calm,
cool and collected,'' he said, ``but when they start trading, calm,
cool and collected doesn't work any more.''
</TEXT>
