<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     10-14 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEERFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They had to change some of the songs at
Deerfield Academy this fall. It hardly seemed appropriate to sing
about the ``sons of Deerfield,'' after 123 girls got to the prep
school.
   And the library sculpture, ``The Deerfield Boy,'' is getting a
sister statue in ``The Deerfield Girl.''
   But students and administrators said those are just cosmetic
changes that don't begin to tell the story of what it means to
reverse 41 years of history as an all-male school.
   ``When you see the girls on campus sometimes you double-take,''
said Ryan Scannell, a 15-year-old junior from Worcester. ``But I'm
used to it now.''
   A few boys have refused to sing the new gender-neutral version
of an old school song, steadfastly singing ``The sons of Deerfield
rally,'' as the first line, instead of ``Deerfield! O Deerfield
rally.''
   One of the new arrivals said she understands those feelings.
   ``There's 40 some odd years of Deerfield that are just sort of
locked up in that song,'' said Rachel Reingold, a 16-year-old
sophomore from Greenwich, Conn., who reports that her welcome was
warmer than she expected.
   Deerfield, a collection of elegant brick buildings clustered in
the historic section of old Deerfield, was founded by Frank L.
Boyden just after the turn of the century. It originally was a coed
school, but in 1948, the school went all-boy after the number of
female students dwindled to just a handful. The changeover back to
coeducation was approved in 1987.
   The headmaster said during the years of planning for the change,
they were told to expect some initial ``academic distraction'' as
boys and girls socialized.
   Students put it more bluntly. ``In two or three more weeks
there'll be, like, couples everywhere,'' Reingold said.
   The 123 girls account for about a fifth of the student body of
502 boarders and 68 day students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
