<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1701EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SniperTrial     10-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sniper Trial,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Sentenced to 30 Years in Rio Grande Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARFA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old boy was sentenced to 30 years
in prison Saturday for fatally shooting a rafter on the Rio Grande
last year.
   A Presidio County jury Friday found Eduardo Rodriguez Pineda
guilty in the attack after a weeklong trial. The jury sentenced
Rodriguez on Saturday. In Texas, the judge or jury may set
punishment at the option of the defendant.
   Authorities said Rodriguez was one of four youths who stood atop
300-foot-high canyon walls overlooking the river on Nov. 19, 1988,
and fired shots that struck and killed Michael Heffley, 40, of
Eastland. His wife, Jamie, and their rafting guide were wounded.
   The shots were fired from the Mexican side of the river, and
under international law, a person standing in one country who
fatally shoots a person in another country can be tried in either
nation.
   ``I am disappointed,'' said Mrs. Heffley. ``They took into
account his age, but he didn't take into account my husband's life.
The Bible says, `Thou shall not kill.'''
   Defense attorneys asked the jury to give Rodriguez probation.
Prosecutors had requested a life sentence.
   Asked if he had anything to say, Rodriguez said through an
interpreter, ``Yes, I just want to ask for forgiveness for that
with which I have been charged.''
   Defense attorneys said they would appeal.
   Two juveniles are in custody in Mexico in connection with the
case. All three are Mexican citizens, but Rodriguez is a legal
resident of the United States and lives in Redford, 60 miles
northwest of Big Bend National Park.
</TEXT>
