<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 1737EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-14 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>40 Bodies Discovered Near Colombo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty bodies, many piled on burning
tires, were found in a nearby town, bringing a weeklong death toll
to more than 200, the government said Saturday.
   Authorities blamed no specific group for the killings, which
occurred since Friday night in and around Kelaniya, five miles
north of Colombo, but pro-government vigilantes were believed
responsible.
   A government statement said the deaths brought to 211 the number
of people killed in the past week, including 121 by vigilantes, 94
by Sinhalese radicals and 36 extremists by security forces.
   Independent sources claimed the toll was about 350, which would
be the most in a week in recent months.
   Sinhalese radicals in the ultranationalist People's Liberation
Front have attacked the Sinhalese-dominated government since the
signing of a peace accord in July 1987 designed to give greater
autonomy to the island nation's Tamil minority. A 6-year-old Tamil
separatist war has left at least 11,000 people dead.
   Human rights groups say the vigilante groups indiscriminately
kill civilians who associate with the Liberation Front and burn
their bodies beyond recognition.
   The government admits the existence of death squads but denies
large scale killings. It blames the front for most of the 5,000
deaths since 1987 in southern and central Sri Lanka, the Sinhalese
heartland.
   The front has rejected President Ranasinghe Premadasa's peace
offers, including repeated invitations to a peace conference that
ended Thursday.
   The front claims to be a Marxist organization but increasingly
has taken up a banner of ultranationalism for the Sinhalese, who
are mostly Buddhists and comprise 75 percent of the country's 16
million people. Tamils account for 18 percent of the population and
are mostly Hindus.
</TEXT>
