<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     10-14 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Provincial Soldiers Charged With Stealing Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two provincial soldiers were
charged Saturday with stealing government file photos of Irish
Republican Army suspects who later became the targets of assassins.
   That brought to eight the number of soldiers from the Ulster
Defense Regiment, a largely Protestant army unit in the British
province, who have been charged in the investigation of leaks from
within the security services.
   People claiming to be Protestant gunmen have said they used such
documents to pick assassination targets, including a Roman Catholic
man slain in August. Two members of the Ulster regiment have been
charged in the murder.
   The two charged Saturday, Lance Cpl. Wallace Francis Andrews,
25, and Pvt. Steven Harris, 20, appeared at a special court in
Lisburn. They are accused of stealing government file photographs
on Aug. 12.
   The documents disappeared from Dunmurry police station in south
Belfast.
   Both soldiers were granted bail of $312.
   Twenty-eight members of the Ulster Defense Regiment were
arrested in raids on homes last Sunday that also turned up
government security documents and ammunition.
   The mainly Catholic IRA has killed 180 regiment members in its
20-year battle to end British rule and unite the province with the
Roman Catholic Republic of Ireland. By police count, 2,759 people
have died in political killings since the violence began in 1969.
