<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-14 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Northeast, Tropical Storm Approaching Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell Saturday in parts of New York state and clouds covered
much of the Northeast, while residents along the Louisiana coast
prepared for Tropical Storm Jerry.
   Thunderstorms north of a warm front curving through the Great
Lakes region and the middle Atlantic Coast states produced golf
ball-sized hail in Grayling in northern lower Michigan and 1-inch
hail at Mio and Hartsville.
   The Gulf Coast region and the southern Atlantic Coast states
were also cloudy, with showers mainly in Georgia and South Carolina.
   Tropical Storm Jerry was about 350 miles south-southwest of New
Orleans on Saturday evening and was moving north-northeast at about
6 mph.
   Skies were partly cloudy across much of the western half of the
country. Sunny skies prevailed from the southern Plains to the Ohio
Valley and temperatures were warming into the 80s.
   High-temperature records for the date were set in Beckley,
W.Va., 78 degrees; Fort Wayne, Ind., 84; and South Bend, Ind., 85.
   The cold spot in the Lower 48 states Saturday morning was
Gunnison, Colo., with a low of 21 degrees.
