<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     10-14 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Trade Representative Sounds Softer Tone in Trade Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said Saturday
that a complete opening of Japan's markets would not eliminate the
two countries' financial imbalances.
   She said the United States and other nations also must reduce
their trade barriers.
   Mrs. Hills told reporters her talks with government and business
officials during her first trip to Japan as the U.S. trade
representative were ``quite constructive. ... There have been no
demands.''
   Japanese officials said Mrs. Hills urged Japan to open its
markets wider to U.S. construction companies, satellites and
supercomputers. In response, Post and Telecommunications Minister
Sempachi Oishi told her five of the eight satellites Japan plans to
launch this year are American-made, the officials said.
   Mrs. Hills said she did not discuss rice imports with Japanese
officials. The Japanese government has strongly resisted demands
from U.S. rice producers that it permit imports of the staple grain.
   Mrs. Hills said other nations, including the United States, also
needed to do more to open their markets.
   ``Every market I can think of has protections. If all of those
were to open up, I can guarantee to you we would have a geometric
increase in worldwide prosperity,'' she said.
   She said she did not believe in a heavy-handed response to
Japanese trade barriers under the ``super 301'' clause of the U.S.
Omnibus Trade Act, which provides for punitive actions against
countries that do not practice free trade.
   Mrs. Hills arrived in Tokyo Thursday after a visit to South
Korea and was to leave for home Sunday morning. On Friday, students
in South Korea protested her visit and U.S. trade pressure.
</TEXT>
