<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-Queen,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Queen Elizabeth II Calls for Global Cooperation to Fight Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II of Britain
Saturday called for more global cooperation to fight pollution,
disease and drugs.
   The queen, who arrived Saturday for a state visit just ahead of
the 46-nation Commonwealth summit, spoke at a banquet given by
Malaysian King Sultan Azlan Shah.
   ``Nobody recognizes more clearly than you yourselves that
progress brings penalties as well as its advantages,'' she said,
citing the growth of this former British colony, which gained
independence in 1957.
   ``Pollution, new and terrible diseases, drugs, are all to some
degree the products of progress with which we all have to
struggle,'' the queen said. ``By cooperation and sharing
experiences we can hope to alleviate the consequences of these
scourges of the modern world.''
   Ahmad Kamil Jaafar, secretary general of the Malaysian Foreign
Ministry, said leaders attending the Commonwealth summit will issue
a declaration on how Britain and its former colonies _ which form
the Commonwealth _ should deal with environmental problems. The
summit begins Wednesday and ends Oct. 24.
   Other issues to be discussed include drug abuse and acquired
immune deficiency syndrome.
   Also Saturday, the queen visited a mosque and had tea with
Selangor state Sultan Salahuddin Shah.
   Sunday she was to attend church services, lay a wreath at the
National Monument, visit a home for the elderly and watch horse
racing at the Turf Club.
   She last visited Malaysia in 1972.
