<HEAD>Tour Bus Flips in Las Vegas, Injuring 42</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 42 injured, cause of accident, quotes, other details.
ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tour bus swerved out of control and flipped
on its side Saturday on a rain-slickened interstate downtown,
injuring all 42 people aboard, officials said.
   The bus overturned around 4 p.m. on the northbound side of
Interstate 15, said Robert Forbuss, president of Mercy Ambulance.
   The 41 passengers and the driver were taken to four hospitals,
Forbuss said. The worst injury reported was a pelvic fracture.
   Scorpio Tours bus driver Jose Luis Figuarera, 51, said in
Spanish through an interpreter that he lost control when he braked
for a car in front of him.
   The bus rolled over on its side, but did not overturn, officials
said. A tractor-trailer rig following the bus swerved out of
control and collided with a car, but no injuries were reported. A
light rain was fallling at the time.
   ``I just saw a lot of cars getting tangled up. Then I saw a
cloud of dust and the bus was in the middle of the cloud of dust
and then it just went over on its side,'' said Clark County
firefighter Malcolm Turner, who was driving home.
   Guests at the nearby Palace Station casino and hotel also saw
the accident, and notified casino security guards, said security
supervisor Sgt. Harold Cook.
   ``I ran out and saw the bus overturned on the highway, about 30
to 35 feet away,'' Cook said. ``People were stopping their cars and
running to the bus.''
   City Fire Department paramedic Gary Pung said, ``A lot of
drivers stopped to help and a lot of the injured were literally
lined up waiting for assistance when ambulances began arriving.''
   Security guards from the U.S. Energy Department's Las Vegas
regional headquarters also helped the injured, paramedics said.
</TEXT>
