<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 2211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     10-14 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syria Troop Issue Stalls Peace Talks; Aoun Threatens Christian Negotiators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's parliamentary deputies
Saturday narrowed their peace talks to the issue of Syria's
military presence, but one military leader said Christian deputies
could be in trouble if they come home with a bad deal.
   In a statement carried by Christian radio stations in Beirut,
Lebanon, Christian Gen. Michel Aoun called on the deputies not to
``make any commitment that would be viewed as a concession on
sovereignty.''
   ``The Lebanese people will have no mercy on anyone who makes
concessions no matter how important he is,'' Auon said.
   The talks, aimed at ending Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war and
revamping the nation's government, entered their third week in this
mountain resort Saturday.
   Lebanon's Christian-dominated system of government was set up
when the country gained independence from France in 1943. At that
time Christians were in the majority, but now Moslems make up 55
percent of the population.
   Conference sources expressed optimism that the Syrian question
could be resolved if Aoun accepts an Arab League guarantee that the
Syrians will withdraw their 40,000 troops from Lebanon under a
two-year timetable.
   The draft peace plan by Arab League mediators envisages the
phased withdrawal of Syrian troops from metropolitan areas to the
eastern Bekaa Valley.
   The final pullout would be left vaguely tied to the end of the
Israeli military presence in the country and a strong central
government in Beirut that would sign a ``security pact'' with Syria.
   Syrian troops are in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate. However, Aoun says they have lost their
mandate by openly siding with the Moslems in the civil war.
   The meeting of the 63 deputies started Sept. 30. The lawmakers
have announced several times they were on the verge of a peace
settlement, only to be frustrated by renewed demands from one side
or the other.
   Said one source, ``They reach a consensus and then get a
telephone call from Beirut, and we are back where we started.''
   Pro-Syrian Shiite Moslem leader Nabih Berri and Druze warlord
Walid Jumblatt have upped the stakes from Beirut each time Aoun's
hard-line Maronite Christians demanded a quicker Syrian pullout and
written guarantees from the Syrian government in Damascus.
   The Moslems have concentrated on the power-sharing formula the
Arab mediators _ Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria _ have outlined
as a charter for national reconciliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
