<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 2214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionDemonstrations 1stLd-Writethru a0622 10-14 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Demonstrations, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>116 Arrested in Anti-Abortion Protest in Chicago</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Boston protest, arrests; picks
up 5th graf, `Those arrested ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 180 people were arrested Saturday at
anti-abortion demonstrations in front of clinics in this city and
Boston, authorities said. Abortion rights activists also rallied in
Boston and Evanston.
   Of about 200 protesters who turned out in Chicago, 116 were
charged with mob action and resisting arrest for blocking the
clinic, said police Cmdr. James Hollandsworth.
   In Boston, 68 anti-abortion demonstrators were arrested on
charges of disorderly conduct, and another was charged with assault
and battery on a police officer, said police Superintendent Ronald
X. Conway.
   More than 300 people, including 75 abortion rights activists,
turned out for the demonstration at a clinic across from the Boston
Common.
   In Illinois, abortion is expected to be a key issue during the
state General Assembly's fall session, and a new bid is being made
to settle an abortion lawsuit scheduled to be heard by the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   ``I personally came out because my mother had five children and
one she aborted. I'm glad that one wasn't me,'' said Star Kolesar,
35, of Chicago, who marched in front of the Chicago clinic carrying
a sign that read, ``I was unwanted and abused, yet I love life.''
   Those arrested sat four-deep in front of the clinic's parking
lot and entrance and were carried away by police, Hollandsworth
said. A smaller group of abortion rights activists demonstrated on
the other side of the street, he said.
   In Evanston, two state legislators urged about 200 pro-choice
activists at a rally to write to lawmakers and tell them that the
abortion-rights view is in the mainstream, said David Gallo,
spokesman for state Rep. Woody Bowman.
   ``What the other side tries to tell legislators is that
pro-choice is not the mainstream stance,'' Bowman said. ``This is
not true. They, the other side, are the extremists.''
   In another development, Attorney General Neil F. Hartigan
scheduled a meeting Monday to try to settle a lawsuit involving a
Rockford abortion clinic that is to be heard by the U.S. Supreme
Court on Dec. 5. The clinic has successfully challenged state rules
governing building specificiation for abortion clinics as being
medically unnecessary.
</TEXT>
