<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineIndictments     10-14 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Indictments,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indictments Brought Against Crew in Record Cocaine Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury charged the crew of a
ship that was carrying a record six tons of cocaine when the Coast
Guard boarded it in the Gulf of Mexico on Oct. 2.
   A woman and eight men were charged Friday with possessing
cocaine with intent to distribute it. Conviction could bring up to
life in prison because of the amount of cocaine involved, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Mike McMahon.
   He said the crew could be charged later with importing cocaine
if papers found on the 185-foot Zedom Sea indicate the drug was
destined for the United States.
   The 12,000 pounds was the largest maritime cocaine seizure by
American authorities, the Coast Guard said.
   The ship, flying under a Panamanian flag, was seized in the gulf
several miles off the Yucatan coast of Mexico. The ship's papers
said it was heading to Tampico, Mexico, but Coast Guard officials
said the course did not appear to be in that direction
   The crew is in federal custody in New Orleans, held without bond.
</TEXT>
