<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--WrongAirfield     10-14 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Wrong Airfield,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wayward Pilot Lands in Hayfield; Crashes On Takeoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YATES CENTER, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot landed on a mowed hayfield he
mistook for a grass airstrip, asked a farmer for directions and
then crashed his plane as he took off.
   Pilot George R. Kern and his passenger, Donnie Spencer, walked
away uninjured Friday from the wreckage of the single-engine Cessna.
   Kern was about a mile away from a grass airstrip outside Yates
Center in southeastern Kansas when he touched down in the hayfield,
officials said.
   ``He went to a farmhouse, asked where he was at and tried to
take off again,'' said Woodson County Deputy Sheriff Howard Kahler.
   A wing clipped a pine tree as Kern took off, and the plane spun
around and crashed into shallow water near the edge of a reservoir,
Kahler said.
   After the crash, Kern went to farmhouse to call authorities,
Kahler said.
</TEXT>
