<FIRST>r a AM-SeriesSwimmers     10-14 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Series Swimmers,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Giants' Fans Swim to Series Opener</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six San Francisco Giants' fans swam 12
miles across San Francisco Bay to the opening game of the World
Series on Saturday, and were greeted with boos from followers of
the Oakland Athletics.
   Swimmer Tim Callahan and his friends climbed out of the water
near the Oakland Coliseum after swimming from the Embarcadero's
Ferry Building _ a trip that took four hours and 54 minutes.
   Callahan and his friends, who also swam the English Channel last
summer, got the idea from San Francisco newspaper columnist Herb
Caen, who recently suggested that if a Bay Bridge World Series
developed, it was inevitable that some wacky Giants fans would
stroke their way to Candlestick Park.
   Swimmer Mike Webb said the group from San Francisco's Dolphin
Club decided to do even better _ make a 12-mile watery jaunt all
the way across the bay.
   ``The wind was a little cold,'' he said. ``We called the water
warm; a lot of people would call it freezing.''
   A couple of boats were on hand to take them back to safer,
friendlier territory. All in all, Callahan said the experience was
``easy, fun.''
   The series marks the first time since 1956 that two teams in the
same metropolitan area have clashed in a World Series and the
meeting has been dubbed ``The Bridge Series'' for the span that
connects the two cities.
</TEXT>
