<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 2350EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ArtContest     10-14 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Art Contest,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Man Wins Top Prize at International Art Exhibition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American scupltor Martin Puryear won
the top prize Saturday at the 20th Sao Paulo Bienal, considered one
of the world's most important international art shows.
   The prize for the country with the best group of art works went
to France.
   Works by more than 150 artists from 42 countries will be on
display through Dec. 10 at the exhibition, which opened Saturday
and is held every two years.
   Puryear, of Chicago, was named the best artist. His exhibit is
comprised of eight large sculptures of different shapes and
patterns made of cedar, steel wire mesh, tar, oak, rattan and
rawhide.
   Jacques Leenhardt, director of the International Art and
Sculpture Center in Paris and one of the five judges, said
Puryear's work ``points to a new direction in sculpture. His work
is abstract, yet at the same time it allows the viewer to interact
with it and create his own images.''
   Puryear was also chosen because of his ``innovative use of
materials that come from primitive cultures,'' Leenhardt said.
   Puryear would only say, ``I am just overwhelmed for myself and
all the people who supported me.''
   He and the French delegation received bronze replicas of an
abstract scuplture by the late Brazilian artist Victor Brecheret.
   The French exhibition contains the works of four artists: Alain
Jacquet, Antonio Semeraro, Jay Chiat and Edouard Merino.
   Leenhardt praised the French work for ``artistic coherence,
quality and diversification and because as a whole they form a good
illustration of contemporary art.''
   The other judges were: Kynaston McShine, senior curator of New
York City's Museum of Modern Art; Guillermo Whitelow, a member of
Argentina's Art Critics Association; Carlos von Schmidt,
international curator of the 20th Sao Paulo Bienal; and Takeshi
Kanasawa, curator of Japan's Hara Museum.
</TEXT>
