<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Hugo-BiggestOak     10-14 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hugo-Biggest Oak,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biggest Shumard Oak Tree Felled During Hurricane Hugo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest Shumard oak tree in the
nation, more than 155 feet tall, was felled during Hurricane Hugo,
national park officials said.
   When last measured in 1983, the tree was 155 feet tall, 20 feet
in circumference and had a crown of 116 feet, said Bob McDaniel,
superintendent of the Congaree Swamp National Monument outside
Columbia, where the tree was located.
   The tree, estimated at 140 to 165 years old, was registered with
the American Forestry Association as the largest of its type in the
country.
   The Shumard oak, one of 24 oak species found in South Carolina,
is distinguished by its rough bark and elongated nut.
   An Overcup oak in the Congaree Swamp listed as the
second-largest of its species in the nation also was felled by the
storm, McDaniel said. It was 123 feet tall, 22 feet in
circumference and had a 48-foot crown.
   The timber industry in South Carolina lost 4.4 million acres of
trees totaling $1.04 billion in the Sept. 21 hurricane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
