<SECOND>AM-BRF--Coastal Cleanup,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Coastal Cleanup Turns Up Trash From 39 Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 433 miles of fishing line,
14 dead sea turtles and trash from 40 nations turned up on Florida
beaches during a coastal cleanup, a conservation group reported.
   The results of the Sept. 23 litter-bashing effort so appalled
some officials they have decided to send a letter to local
governments urging them to do more to stop littering.
   ``I was pretty discouraged and disgusted with the things we
picked up,'' said Jan Platt, a Hillsborough County Commissioner who
chairs the Agency on Bay Management.
   The statewide cleanup attracted 14,000 volunteers who bagged and
labeled more than 200 tons of trash, said Heidi Lovett of the
non-profit Center for Marine Conservation, which organizes three
such cleanups a year.
   Litter from 39 foreign countries, including Mexico, the Soviet
Union and Germany, was collected. Officials say the trash probably
was dumped overboard by foreign vessels and swept by ocean currents
to Florida.
</TEXT>
