<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is
reassuring the nation the largest decline in the stock market since
the 1987 crash will not hurt the real economy that provides
Americans with jobs and stable prices.
   ``The outlook is good for continued moderate growth,'' said
Brady, who issued a statement two hours after the market closed
Friday.
   He was the only senior government official to comment on the
stunning almost 191-point drop of the Dow Jones industrial average.
   President Bush refused to answer reporters' shouted questions
while boarding a helicopter at the White House on his way to his
Camp David retreat in Maryland.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and President Bush are facing two
impending budget struggles following Senate passage of a $14
billion deficit-reduction bill that was stripped clean of billions
of dollars of spending items and tax breaks.
   The chamber's 87-7 passage of the fiscal 1990 deficit-cutting
legislation late Friday set the stage for what could be difficult
negotiations between the Senate and House on a compromise version
of the bill.
   Unless Bush signs the compromise into law by Monday _ impossible
because House members are away for the weekend _ $16 billion in
defense and domestic spending cuts will take effect that day. The
fiscal year began Oct. 1.
   The deal worked out between Democratic and Republican leaders
also left the bill minus a capital gains tax cut that has been a
priority for Bush, putting off that partisan showdown.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany reportedly will allow hundreds more
refugees to leave for the West and has freed most pro-democracy
demonstrators, although Communist leader Erich Honecker rejected
talks on reform with the opposition.
   Party sources and Western analysts speculated the 77-year-old
Honecker's downfall could come soon, although no official word has
surfaced of a possible leadership change.
   Since July, about 50,000 East Germans have fled to West Germany
and at least 70,000 others have emigrated or refused to return
after being allowed to visit West Germany. Most refugees complained
that demands for reform and greater democracy got nowhere in
Honecker's hard-line regime.
   East Germany conceded Friday that the exodus has cut
significantly into its labor force.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARBO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole steered the
heads of Pittston Co. and the United Mine Workers to their first
meeting since a bitter strike began six months ago, saying ``it's
time to start the healing.''
   Mrs. Dole said Friday she believed face-to-face talks between
Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas and UMW President Richard Trumka
were the only way to break the long stalemate.
   ``I'm not a mediator. I'm not here to say I have the answer to
this complex problem, but I do feel now it is time to see if we can
facilitate the bargaining process,'' she said. ``Ultimately, it has
to be resolved between the private parties.''
   The labor secretary announced she had arranged the meeting for
this afternoon in her Washington office after a fact-finding trip
to the coal fields.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he still wants Panamanian
ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega out of power but that doesn't mean
he's giving a ``carte blanche'' for use of U.S. military troops to
help remove him.
   Bush, continuing to defend his decision not to intervene in the
failed coup attempt by Panamanian military officers last week,
said, ``I wouldn't mind using force if it could be done in a
prudent manner.''
   But, he said, ``I hope I would never be reckless enough as a
commander in chief to make a blanket commitment to use of force
without knowing the facts regarding some coup attempt.''
   He called complaints that he should have used military power to
back up his repeated calls for Panamanians to oust Noriega ``a
stupid argument that some very erudite people make.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>McCLELLAN AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robot with a neutron
ray gun that spots deadly corrosion in Air Force jets could become
an important weapon in ensuring the safety of the nation's aging
commercial airliners.
   The new, computer-controlled machine is being programmed to test
F-111 fighter-bombers and other planes inside a specially built
hangar at this Sacramento-area base.
   Even before it goes into day-to-day use in mid-1990, the Federal
Aviation Administration has commissioned a study to see if versions
of the $7.3 million hangar would be practical for use on civilian
airliners.
   The new machine can scan an entire airliner in a period of
hours, zeroing in on problem spots, say the private engineers who
designed it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The verdict's in from experts who dug up the
common grave of five Colorado gold prospectors to see who did them
in and ate them up: Alferd Packer was the murderer with an appetite
for his victims.
   ``Guilty as sin,'' intoned James E. Starrs, a professor of law
and forensic science who led an expedition to Lake City, Colo., to
show what experts in archeology, anthropology, pathology and
firearms could learn about misdeeds committed 115 years ago.
   Starrs said Friday the bones provided scientific evidence that
prove Packer ``beyond the shadow of a doubt'' murdered his
colleagues, marooned in the Rocky Mountains during the murderous
winter of 1874, and ate their flesh to stay alive.
   Packer, accused of killing his fellow prospectors in 1974, was
convicted of murder in 1883 and of five charges of manslaughter
three years later when the first conviction was overturned on a
technicality.
</TEXT>
