<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv16   10-14 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv16,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, Oct. 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Let's Hear It From the Stock Market: What's Up?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The news stunned some stock analysts who had
aniticipated earnings of about $50 million for the quarter. Too
high, suggested a Chrysler executive, ``I doubt we did much better
than break even.''
   There could very well be more shocks of that sort in coming
months, since the stock market has tended to ignore a deterioration
of corporate earnings that began early in the second quarter of the
year.
   The longer term trend is there to be examined, but many
investors appear to ignore it. Meanwhile, their sense of well-being
is secured by reports from many companies showing that, in spite of
a sluggish economy, they are doing well.
   On the day Robert Miller Jr., Chrysler chief financial officer,
estimated negatively on his company's third-quarter earnings,
Coca-Cola reported a 20.9 percent earnings surge and General
Electric a jump of 16 percent.
   Glittering reports of that sort, especially from two of
America's premier companies, are bound to attract the attention of
those who pray for a rising market. But they also obscure the
condition of the majority of corporations.
   For the latter, earnings have lost a lot of momentum. In 1988,
profits of companies in the Standard &amp; Poor's composite index rose
36 percent. The rate fell to 22 percent (over the prior year) in
the first quarter of 1989. In the second quarter, the
year-over-year rise declined to under 5 percent.
   Those rates still leave corporate America making a profit, but
the trend is clear. It is especially clear in certain categories
such as aerospace, apparel, automotive, electronics, metals,
oil-gas and recreation.
   And some well-known companies suffered not just declines in the
upward progress of their profits, but actual losses. In
electronics, for example, Wang reported a loss of $375 million and
Control Data a loss of $497 million.
   Such numbers usually are sufficient to call investor attention
to a problem, and they have. But the concern seems limited to the
specific companies more than to the industry, and to the industry
rather than to the whole market.
   The stock market is believed by many to be a good economic
forecaster, the premise being that investors aren't inclined to
needlessly risk their capital, and so wouldn't be investing if the
next six months or so didn't look good.
   True, you can find few forecasters with arguments that support a
sizable downturn in the economy, but there also are few who foresee
a big increase over 1989. There are many who believe gains in
corporate profits will be small.
   DRI-McGraw-Hill, whose economic projections are used by many
companies, expects after-tax profits to be down sharply in the
first two quarters, based on comparisons with the same quarters a
year earlier.
   Thereafter, it expects an upward trend right through 1991. But
not until the second quarter of that year _ 18 months from now _
does it foresee the level of profits achieved early this year.
   As the stock market plays tag with new highs, therefore, the
pressing question it presents for your consideration is this: Is it
looking six months ahead _ or perhaps two years? Or is it perhaps
confused?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
