<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv16   10-14 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 16,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Some See Brighter Days for Oil Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They starred in the '70s and stumbled in the
'80s. Now Wall Street seems to be warming up again toward energy
stocks as the 1990s approach.
   ``The oil industry's long dry spell appears to be ending,''
declares the Merrill Lynch Market Letter in its current issue.
   ``We think it is giving way to an uptrend that will see all the
major facets of the business _ exploration and production
activities as well as refining and marketing operations _ do well
simultaneously in the years ahead.''
   At another large investment firm, Dean Witter Reynolds, analyst
John Connolly says: ``At long last energy fundamentals look decent.
We now believe this group can significantly influence the success
or failure of a portfolio.''
   Connolly, like many another market-watcher, had been
recommending that investment managers keep their energy holdings
well below the proportionate weight the group carries in the
popular indexes of stock prices.
   Now, he says, ``we have canceled our deep underweighting and
opted, for the first time in years, for a slightly overweighted
position.''
   Even the most ardent energy bulls don't expect investors
suddenly to rush into a sector of the market that has produced so
many disappointments for so long.
   But they do foresee at least a gradual recognition of what they
describe as brightening prospects for both energy demand and energy
prices.
   ``The demand for oil has increased since 1985 and now is more
than 51 million barrels a day, a level last seen 10 years ago,''
Merrill Lynch says.
   ``We think demand will increase at an average annual rate of 1
million barrels a day over the next few years and that prices will
trend higher, especially if supplies from countries that are not
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries begin
to decline.''
   Ah yes, OPEC _ the powerful cartel that was supposed to keep
pushing oil prices higher and higher for the indefinite future
after the energy shocks of the 1970s in the industrialized world.
   When market conditions got tough, it turned out there were some
deep cracks behind that group's supposedly united front.
   But now, Connolly argues, OPEC's leading members have maneuvered
themselves into a position where only a few of them need to
practice restraint in their production policies to tip the balance
of supply and demand in their favor.
   Furthermore, he adds, ``the most significant development in the
next few years will be a pronounced output decline by the world's
largest producer, the Soviet Union.''
   Along with improving business conditions, analysts say, might
come revived takeover interest in energy companies. Says Merrill
Lynch, ``higher valuations for refining and marketing facilities
have boosted the asset values of many oil companies.''
   Despite all such arguments, many skeptics remain. Investors
trying to spot a rebound in the oil industry's fortunes have been
frustrated repeatedly since the mid-1980s.
   In his report on the subject, Connolly says he was not an easy
convert to the cause.
   ``We have hesitated to commit to the energy area all year,'' he
says. ``In fact, we have hesitated for several years now, proving
that he who hesitates is not always lost.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Oct. 16.</NOTE>
</DOC>
