<DOCNO> AP891014-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-14-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-TV-SiberianGlasnost Adv16   10-14 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV-Siberian Glasnost, Adv 16,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Oct. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Documentary Gives Glimpse Inside Siberia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Show airs Oct. 16.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Siberian villager led an American
interviewer into his home and, safely out of view of his neighbors,
started talking about freedom in the Altai Mountains far from
Moscow.
   ``This is the only place in the whole world where a person can
feel himself being free, can feel himself being original, to be
himself, to be his own person,'' he said in Russian. ``That is the
Altai spirit and that is what I'm proud of.''
   But Soviet authorities, like the invading armies that have swept
through southern Siberia since the 8th century B.C., now are
encroaching upon his lifestyle: electricity, a day care facility,
television.
   That revealing bit of glasnost (openness) appears near the end
of ``Hard Labor in Siberia,'' a documentary that premieres Monday
on the Discovery Channel. It was one of many unexpected events an
American river-running team encountered in Siberia in August 1988.
   ``That did surprise us,'' the program's writer-director, John
Armstrong, recalled in a recent interview. The Altai villager,
Armstrong said, had been reluctant to speak initially for fear his
neighbors would think he was an informant. Then he opened up on his
government.
   ``He was saying we are the freest people in the world, we have
the freest spirit, and he's proud of it, and he doesn't like the
Soviet Union. He doesn't like them coming in and meddling,''
Armstrong said.
   The villager also had his own views about America.
   ``He just cracked us up when he said `This is the Miami of the
Soviet Union.' To him Miami meant freedom,'' Armstrong added.
   Despite its title, there are no Soviet gulags in ``Hard Labor in
Siberia.'' The labor was in navigating the Bashkaus River, an angry
ribbon of water that surges through the Altai Mountains.
   The film documents the first attempt by a Western group to
traverse the Bashkaus, said to be one of the toughest stretches of
whitewater in the world.
   As an adventure film, ``Hard Labor in Siberia'' packs a wallop.
But Armstrong clearly is interested in more than just man against
nature; he also pits the Western notion of lock-step communist
states against the reality of the independent Altai people and the
three outspoken Soviet river runners who led the trip.
   ``They were just like us, just in terms of the way they
related,'' Armstrong said of the Soviet boaters. ``They could care
less about what their government was saying. In fact, they were
even suspicious of (Soviet President Mikhail) Gorbachev,''
Armstrong said.
   The film is a constant clash of opposites: frenzied water
bashing immovable rocks; big-city Soviets confronting agrarian
Siberians; high-tech U.S. equipment vs. low-tech but inventive
Soviet hardware; and ``can do'' Americans challenged by cautious
Russian bureaucrats.
   The expedition began badly. The Soviet organizers,
Sovintersport, were unsure of the abilities of their Western
visitors and suddenly decided they should do a less dangerous river.
   But once Sovintersport authorities were out of sight, the
Americans persuaded their Soviet guides that they were capable of
tackling the Bashkaus.
   ``The Soviets aren't geared up for tourists running their rivers
in the first place,'' Armstrong said. ``They thought (the Bashkaus)
would be too dangerous _ they didn't know what we were capable of
handling and they didn't want any bodies on their hands.''
   A Soviet river runner had died on the Bashkaus just a few days
earlier, bringing the death count to seven since the river first
was run in 1977.
   An American raft nearly sank when it became wedged in rocks, and
the American kayakers often looked to be in danger of being
swallowed by heart-stopping vortices of water.
   The Soviets were adept with their catamaran-like boats that had
two inflated canvas pontoons joined by tubing and birchbark straps.
The Soviets balanced astride the pontoons bronc-busting style.
   A final surprise awaited the expedition at the end of their
journey: a Soviet film crew was in the Altai village shooting a
gold robbery ``Western'' based on a Jack London short story.
   And even in this remote corner of the world, the Soviet film
makers traveled in style _ with a sauna.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
